question_list.author: SheilaB
question_list.text:
Uncle Wayne always gives me a pain.
His ideas are vain and inane.
He's both asinine (fatuous)
And a gas bag who's flatuous.
I treat the old fool with disdain.
question_list.question: What is wrong with Uncle Wayne's ideas?
question_list.answer: Uncle Wayne's ideas are vain and inane.
alternate_answers:
Uncle Wayne's ideas are considered vain and inane,
He's both asinine and flatuous, causing disdain.

Based on the limerick, there are a few things wrong with Uncle Wayne's ideas:

1. They are described as "vain and inane" - meaning they are empty, worthless, and foolish.

2. He is characterized as being "asinine" - which means stupid or foolish. 

3. He is also described as being a "gas bag" who is "flatuous" - implying his ideas are full of hot air and empty rhetoric.

4. The narrator treats Uncle Wayne with "disdain" - showing a strong dislike and lack of respect for his ideas.

Overall, the limerick portrays Uncle Wayne's ideas as being foolish, stupid, and unworthy of serious consideration. The narrator clearly has a very negative view of his uncle's thought processes and opinions.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
"Pomoxis, your opercle's spiny."
"You human, I'd say, 'Bite my hiney,'
Except that you would."
"Sure! You taste yummy good —
You're a crappie. Now, don't be so whiney."

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
We were naked. Said she: "Why delay so?
And your lust—why's it fading away so?"
She had hair on her back
And she smelled like a yak.
Was the feeling displeasant? I'd say so.

limerick_list.author: Michael Toalster
limerick_list.text:
Sister Mary was bald (had no hair).
As she sat in the hairdresser's chair,
She said "Just a short coif,
Will be really enough."
So he tailored a skullcap with care.

limerick_list.author: Jonathan Caws-Elwitt
limerick_list.text:
You tell me that you never brag,
That boasting just isn't your bag.
When you claim to be humble,
My darling, you fumble.
I'm on to you — ain't it a drag!

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
A reality show gave a thrill
As chaos ensued at the mill
With these woodworking fools
Laying waste with their tools
And the crowd screaming, "Drill, baby, drill!"

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
That new outbuilding (you think the best)
Doesn't harmonise well with the rest
Of the house. Out of place,
It's a spot on the face;
An excrescence whose sight I detest.

limerick_list.author: DenmarK
limerick_list.text:
My programming life was once cursed.
Lots more memory, please, was my thirst.
What resolved half my trouble?
The magnetised bubble,
But lots of cheap RAM made it burst.

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
If you're sending a note to L.A.,
Don't forget to address it this way:
Write Los Angeles down,
Add a zip for the town.
In between write the state code: CA.

limerick_list.author: Snowy Owl
limerick_list.text:
Those who seek expertise arbitrational
Tell me troubles in tones conversational.
Then they pay me my price—
And ignore my advice.
It's a hazard, I fear, occupational.

limerick_list.author: Peter Meyer
limerick_list.text:
A cryptographer tried to decode
(Or decrypt) an enciphered old ode,
And he worked on the script
Till he lay in his crypt—
'Encrypted', and thus à la mode.

limerick_list.author: woodfostersmith
limerick_list.text:
Bromouracil molecules may
Sub for thymine in one's DNA.
Their structure is such
That it doesn't take much
To put chromosomes in disarray.

limerick_list.author: neilski
limerick_list.text:
A British Columbian said:
"Where's the place that I lay down my head?
No, it's not Bogotá
And not Leamington Spa,
But it's fine old Vancouver instead!"

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Thirty years Joseph hid from the government,
So he should have perceived what his lover meant
When she cautioned, "I know
Of your history, Joe,"
But he laughed. The result? His discoverment.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Areopagus, I must report
Is a word of the Ancient Greek sort.
It was named for the hill
Where it stood, and it will
Be remembered as Athens' high court.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
After stealing my aunt's Stradivarius,
The burglar's defense was hilarious!
He declared with great poise
That his picklocks were toys,
When it's clear that his tools were burglarious.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Garish trappings must all disappear.
They seem tactless—and you? Insincere.
No more coveting cool;
Let propriety rule.
I can help you decrassify, dear.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
You shop at a membership store
With astonishing bargains galore.
But you can't get just one:
You must buy by the ton
For your family of three-hundred-four.

limerick_list.author: Aliza
limerick_list.text:
When a polygon's complex, it's not
Mathematically simple; it's got
Some edges that cross,
Or a hole (what a loss!)
Like that "No Hunting" sign that you shot.

limerick_list.author: David
limerick_list.text:
You are seeking the meaning of bow-wow?
Even infants can point out a "wow-wow"!
If you're still in the dark
That it's dogs and their bark,
Maybe you and your parents should pow-wow.

limerick_list.author: StephenGold
limerick_list.text:
Though the lady's offensive and coarse,
With the face of an ill-tempered horse,
The size of her dower
Caused passion to flower
(But it couldn't prevent the divorce).

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
This month's ovum's released, like as not
Hitting nothing but fimbria. What
Fate waits for it hinges
On chance past these fringes,
And that sure but implausible shot.

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
Dallas, Texas: the site on the day
That Lee Harvey dispatched JFK.
Did he act all alone?
Was he merely a drone?
A conspiracy, some people say.

limerick_list.author: Thomas Taylor
limerick_list.text:
When Germans and Austro-Hungarians
United with Turks and Bulgarians,
Their enemies pressed
From the east and the west —
They were Central, these arch-militarians.

limerick_list.author: creelbm
limerick_list.text:
Sum the absolute value of terms
In a series.  If finite, no squirms
'Cause you've seen the emergence
Of absolute convergence.
It's an answer math theory confirms.

limerick_list.author: Doug Aldridge
limerick_list.text:
Kirk finished his planned surface stay
And returned in a "particle" way.
This command starts his travel
(Makes his atoms unravel):
"Beam me up!" ends a normal Trek day.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
"It's a science: how flowers can cluster,"
Blared bellicose botanist Buster.
"Anthotaxy, in essence,
Describes inflorescence!"
(Declaimed with defiance and bluster.)

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Chenopodium album? Do tell.
I confess I don't know it that well.
But no matter how great,
Let me tell you here straight:
It's a dud next to Bat Out of Hell.

limerick_list.author: Charles Silliman
limerick_list.text:
Little ditto marks: simple and neat.
   "       "         "     : aren't they a treat?
Place them right below text,
    "        "     there to show next
Where each word, up above, should repeat.

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
I've a butt of fine wine — take a peep.
Once it's opened, you know it won't keep.
Have a glass my dear, do;
Hark, it's calling to you:
"Drink me up and I'll help you to sleep."

limerick_list.author: Mary
limerick_list.text:
To compensate parents,  I'd leave,
As repayment for joys that they weave,
A brief time for reflection
And sharing affection—
Just a space for deep breaths, Christmas Eve.

limerick_list.author: Brian Cairns
limerick_list.text:
JS Bach, to his wife, on retiring:
"My new fugue needs a little inspiring—
Come, my dear, let's be wild,
And risk just one more child!
Be the Joy of this German's Desiring!"

limerick_list.author: C. H. Carpenter
limerick_list.text:
In their habitat, haddock (marine),
Or Atlantic red perch can be seen.
This bergylt's head is spiny.
Fish are mottled when tiny,
But when grown, rosefish glow with a sheen.

limerick_list.author: Paperdragon
limerick_list.text:
Cyberslacking, I guess, is not right;
I'm not working, I'm shirking tonight.
My net surfing's a crime
During company time —
I've just found a great limerick site.

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
The UK's clever MPs designed
The early day motion, a kind
That has helped draw attention
To matters they mention
That should be engaging the mind.

limerick_list.author: James Dobson
limerick_list.text:
Filled with love, I had planned in advance
That I'd ask my new beau for a dance.
"Oh, I'm sorry, my dear,
The dance orchestra's here.
I'm conducting, and can't change my stance."

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
A marvelous mammal's the beaver,
And, oh, what an overachiever!
This builder of dams
Fills the river with jams,
And its name means . . . a hat or a Cleaver.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
I could hear the entire escouade
Gasconading aloud in the quad.
At the acting-troupe fest,
Their small group was the best.
(That squad's great, too, in rodomontade.)

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
A calmative helps you to calm,
Providing an internal balm—
Inordinate action
Reduced to a fraction
Ensuring you come to no harm.

limerick_list.author: Chuck Folkers
limerick_list.text:
The police made a note in the blotter:
They've arrested a slippery otter.
The report also says
He was wearing a fez;
They suspect he's a terrorist plotter.

limerick_list.author: FunkyTuba
limerick_list.text:
My valence is one. That will do.
A radical ring, well, who knew?
Should this still not suffice,
Then to be more precise:
I am C6H5CH2.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Bailing out at this point's a mistake.
First consider the profits we'll make.
Popularity's spreading
For our pre-flavored breading.
And that brand name? Come on—Shake 'n Bake!

limerick_list.author: Snowy Owl
limerick_list.text:
An astute, analytical guy
Earned repute as a suit (FBI).
He suggested a scheme
Whose success was extreme:
'Twas a sly sting, a spy ring to fry.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Animalia is sculpture of cats
Or iguanas or horses or rats
Or flamingos or monkeys
Or tigers or donkeys
Or weasels or vampire bats.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Echolalia? You seem in a daze,
Looking crazed, as your eyes have a glaze.
You can't make yourself clear,
But whatever you hear,
You repeat—every word, every phrase.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
I don't trust a bar neat as a pin;
They'll pour belly wash, not honest gin:
Why should anyone choose
Their deplorable booze?
The beer's dreary; the rum rots your skin.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
I believed I could get to first base;
You resisted — I'm shamed, out of place.
I screwed up; I can't see
Why the joke is on me.
I'm embarrassed — there's egg on my face.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
I told Jed, "I believes you been tooken
Them there catfish I spent all day hookin'."
Well, Jed swore it weren't he
As he stomped on my knee—
I could see my straight leg quickly crooken.

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
At a bus stop, a bus ought to stop;
At request stops, you might have to pop
Out a hand (if you're hailing)
Or, button availing,
Go buzz ("off the bus let me hop").

limerick_list.author: Type A
limerick_list.text:
Electron spectroscopy shows
Just which atoms are present. Suppose
That this fellow, Auger,
Hated chemistry — they
Would have named it for whom? Heaven knows.

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
Here's a factual account of my day:
Did the ironing, threw rubbish away,
Washed the walls and the ceiling —
All facts and no feeling.
Dear Diary, there's more I could say ...

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
I don't wish to encroach on your me time,
Which, in turn, is my own let-you-be time,
But I've made a fresh brew
That I can't leave to stew
So I distantly mention it's teatime.

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
My car is an oldie but goodie.
All the chicks, they are wonderin', "Could he
Take me for a ride?"
And I've always replied,
"Do you know how to polish a woodie?"

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
It's an honor that fits like a glove:
Famous actors receiving above-
the-title laudation;
A film name's location
Comes after the actors we love.

limerick_list.author: Kevin
limerick_list.text:
John Betjeman wrote he was sorry
To see that old Bath was a quarry,
Where people were starting
To wreck it by carting
It "off by developer's lorry".

limerick_list.author: Steve Andersen
limerick_list.text:
It's more subtle than having arthritis,
This condition called descemetitis.
Inflammation that's smack
On my cornea's back
Gives me psychosomatic gastritis.

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
A comet hit London—kerPOW!
Said the last one alive, "Holy cow.
Hope and glory have passed.
I'm the first and the last...
I'm the alpha and omega now."

limerick_list.author: David Schildkret
limerick_list.text:
A city on high's the Acropolis;
It stands far above the metropolis.
Here temples abound
Upon Greek sacred ground,
And the gods are the principal populace.

limerick_list.author: Carol June Hooker
limerick_list.text:
Students suffer conditions impeding
Their grasp of the knowledge they're needing.
Integration of art
Links the brain and the heart
And improves comprehension of reading.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
For a substance occurring in tar,
This acridine goes pretty far.
If you open your eyes,
You will see it in dyes
And where'er pharmaceuticals are.

limerick_list.author: mrsrev
limerick_list.text:
I was lying one day in the sun
When my mother said, "Listen up, hon!
You apply cocoa butter,
Or tomorrow you'll mutter
You're burned from the sun. Quickly! Run!"

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
Being so claustrophobic means Claire
Must enrol for some therapy, where
She'll be taught how to deal
With how small places feel
When she's desperate for wide space and air.

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
An offspring of ravens broke laws,
And exposed his behavioral flaws.
When his punishment brings
Him to ground, clips his wings,
He asks "Why?"  And the ravens croak, "Caws!"

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Joe said, "Pols were at each other's throats —
Enraged over rules about votes."
There was "loss of decorum
By Byrd and Santorum.
Result? Loss of quorum," he notes.

limerick_list.author: mrsrev
limerick_list.text:
My daughter loves all things gymnastic,
And her tumbling is rather fantastic.
All her moves far eclipse
All my jumps or your flips.
She is flexible, just like elastic.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
I once knew a woman named Gail
Whose alopecoid mystique I'll unveil:
Nimble quickness combined
With a devious mind,
A sharp nose and a long bushy tail.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
I don't really look where I'm walking,
Sometimes steady in pace, sometimes balking,
As I amble, half dead,
Writing rhymes in my head—
Lips may move, but you can't hear me talking.

limerick_list.author: Anonymity
limerick_list.text:
Ergosterol stubbornly dwells
In the membrane of all fungal cells.
It's in yeast. It's in mold.
It's the sterol, I'm told,
That an azole-based medicine quells.

limerick_list.author: metallel
limerick_list.text:
A limerick's defective if you
Choose to stop when you finish line two.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Love my boastfulness, folks?  Yes, I rate
Myself Blowhard Supreme.  I can state
No one brags more than I!
(Except Trump, that is why
I just lost the "Best Braggart" debate.)

limerick_list.author: hwindle
limerick_list.text:
An accordion door in that room!
But excitement soon shifted to gloom.
Just a door that folds back
When it opens?  Alack,
Then no polkas at all, I presume?

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The company turned off my cable.
I have no more TV; I'm unable
To watch any station,
Or find consolation—
So I cry on my new console table.

limerick_list.author: Nick Szymanski
limerick_list.text:
What will make your stiff style more elastic?
The word order that's known as chiastic.
Just, whatever you say,
Make it a b b a:
"Dull is Wordsworth, while Keats is fantastic!"

limerick_list.author: Mad Kane
limerick_list.text:
You lied in your last deposition,
Further weak'ning your flimsy position.
I've been fleeced, I can see—
It's apparent to me—
So an out-of-court deal ain't my mission.

limerick_list.author: Kevin
limerick_list.text:
This dyarchy known as Andorra
Features skiing, old churches and flora.
Here a bishop from Spain
Holds a share of the reign.
So does France. That's a part of its aura.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
My son brings his friends up to date,
Introduces the family slate:
"The nice lady's my mother,
And that's my big brother."
Big, in this case: age six, three-foot-eight.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
That gee lost five gees on a gee
That ran like a slug. Seemed to be
Under five gees, or drugged
(All geed up). I'd'a slugged
The damn tipster, if it had been me.

limerick_list.author: PGS
limerick_list.text:
Young boys and young girls like to play
Both with toys and each other, I'd say.
Elder boys playing games
With most beautiful dames
See fair game in fair ladies, for prey.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
My grandfather posed me a riddle,
"What's curvy but slim in the middle,
And sings when you pluck it?"
I guessed, but (my luck!) it
Was meant to describe a bass fiddle.

limerick_list.author: psh
limerick_list.text:
In a dock receipt, carriers may
		 State agreement to promptly convey,
		 By named ship or a barge,
		 Shippers' goods small or large —
		To commence once it's "anchors aweigh."

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
I'm a scumbag, a maggot, a flea —
Yeah, but don't disappreciate me.
Don't  deride or despise me,
Pooh-pooh or chastise me.
Babe, don't say "We're finished, whoopee!"

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
Whoa! My brakes don't work. How can that be?
Cool and calm, I must stay, yessiree.
Now to stop this car quick,
What's the best path to pick?
I'll cool-headedly aim at that tree.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Jesus nailed to a cross made of wood
Made a scene the boy misunderstood:
"If Good Friday," he sighed,
"Is the day Jesus died,
Can you tell me just why that day's good?"

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"A calendarer's someone who lists,
But a calenderer," Michael insists,
"Works with paper or cloth!"
Mike will frequently froth
At the mouth as he clenches his fists.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
Warm the cockles, they say, of one's heart.
Mollusks?  No.  The ventricular part
(From corrupting the Latin
Term cochleae).  That, in
A snail shell, explains it.  Feel smart?

limerick_list.author: Joanna Keene
limerick_list.text:
Our gas furnace, my mom always said,
If kicked, would explode: we'd be dead.
I for sure never tried that;
I think that she lied; that
Is just a tale children are fed.

limerick_list.author: Jane Auerbach
limerick_list.text:
An odd guy joined our game and he'd greet all
The players but looked like he'd cheat all.
When we played Texas hold 'em,
All night he'd just fold 'em,
Not raisin'. Now shucks, don't that beat all?

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
When she's bargaining, Tessa's obsessive,
Now languid, now firmly aggressive:
Half crown by half crown,
She'll keep beating you down,
Changing tack like a manic-depressive.

limerick_list.author: Mary
limerick_list.text:
There were Cimbri who lived long ago
On the west half of Jutland, although,
When they came down to Gaul
Against Rome, they lost all.
They are gone—there's not much more to know.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
My advice — my astute commonition —
Results from my sharp intuition.
Your false commination
(Your sham derogation)
Sounds stupid in juxtaposition.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Though you injured the nerve in the past,
All the burning and pain seem to last.
We call it causalgia,
A type of neuralgia.
Seek medical treatment, and fast!

limerick_list.author: Graham Lester
limerick_list.text:
The languages Austroasiatic
Would make a keen linguist ecstatic.
What joy to explore
A full hundred and more —
All awesomely idiomatic!

limerick_list.author: Basingstoke
limerick_list.text:
My friend had a phobia fearful
Named anupta-. She called me, all tearful,
"I'll never be wed!"
Then she met her beau Fred,
And I now get a much diff'rent earful.

limerick_list.author: Taillefer
limerick_list.text:
Last time at the bookshop I picked
Up an etymological dict.,
And it told me that sure
Is French-Latin segur—
To be sure, it's the first book I nicked.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
The cruciform veg is a beaut.
With turnips, you eat leaf and root.
The bud (not the flower)
Is broccoli's power.
It's all sounding brassica. Toot!

limerick_list.author: Workshop
limerick_list.text:
At the camping site: no vacant pitch
For my tent, so they asked me to switch
To the campsite next door.
So I left, rather sore,
And en route ended up in a ditch.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
There are times my intestine just purrs,
But more often it rumbles and stirs
Like a cauldron a-bubble.
With gut-rumbling trouble,
Just one borborygm rarely occurs.

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
Is a culture so terribly strange
Whose traditions are subject to change?
Some begin, others end.
Evolution's our friend,
As it helps to extend custom's range.

limerick_list.author: bob killian
limerick_list.text:
Folks from Minsk shouted out, "Let's break loose
From the USSR's harsh abuse!"
But still it's soul-crushin'
To be Belorussian,
In despotic and gray Belarus.

limerick_list.author: Bob Colonna
limerick_list.text:
As she trundles 'er pushcart, "Oh, 'ark at 'er!"
A whisper comes out of the dark at 'er,
"She calls out as she walks,
Ink and charcoal she 'awks.
She's the bleedin' Whitechapel black marketer."

limerick_list.author: Meg Beagle
limerick_list.text:
Time to yawn and then open your eyes!
Time to leap out of bed, to arise!
You must earnestly strive
To look sharp and alive
Lest The New York Times note your demise.

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
When the weather is frosty or rainy,
I like (yes, it's true, I am zany)
To curl up with a book
Snug in bed with a chook
(Though the term I prefer is galaney).

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
To demyelinate someone's nerves,
This disease strips the padding  that serves
To protect. The distress
That is caused by MS
Is dysfunction no person deserves.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Let me make, without any coercion,
This firm diagnostic assertion:
My boss is a guy
With intense CRI,
Meaning "cranial-rectal insertion."

limerick_list.author: art bates
limerick_list.text:
We've a Labrador dog; he's a case
With a pedigree. Odd? Just a trace.
He abhors getting wet,
And a trip to the vet
Brings to mind parts he cannot replace.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
The word earthshock is one you can use
To mean "earthquake." To me, this is news.
Into Scrabble? I'd say
It's a great word to play
When your rack is devoid of all Q's.

limerick_list.author: mrsrev
limerick_list.text:
I'm a single conservative, mate,
And I'm picky about whom I'll date.
So if we should dine,
I'll decline to drink wine,
And you must have me home before eight.

limerick_list.author: PGS
limerick_list.text:
Das Kraut is a veggie, the cabbage;
It's grown and then gathered by "grabbage."
A "Kraut" is a German,
As Kohl (Helmut, Herman?)
Or Zuse, the "Krautish" Charles Babbage?

limerick_list.author: J. E. Pettit
limerick_list.text:
My son is a master of noise,
And all that he sees, he destroys.
His actions are draining,
But I'm not complaining;
I love him—and boys will be boys.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
I check for the time with a smile
At the hands on my analog dial.
The digital watches
I tried showed just blotches
Or zeros. I ended the trial.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
"Common knowledge suggests," proclaims Louis,
 "Universally known."  I say, "Phooey!"
We all know it's true
There are always a few
Who don't get the message.  (Or do we?)

limerick_list.author: alan meyer
limerick_list.text:
Class,  aasvogel's the Word of the Day.
It's a vulture that thrives on decay.
Now a little used word
For a carrion bird —
A keen-eyed, six-foot-wide bird of prey.

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
A beagle was one with sharp eyes
And keen nose — what you'd want of your spies.
Long before Britain's police force,
He'd help to increase force
In collaring criminal guys.

limerick_list.author: HANG player
limerick_list.text:
There was an old gasman, named Peter,
Who never checked gas by the meter.
He applied his long nose
To a hole in the hose.
His widow, I think, they call Rita.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
If you step on the tail of your pet,
He may howl and become quite upset,
But don't let him escape;
You should get him on tape,
For creating musique that's concrète!

limerick_list.author: Harris Risman
limerick_list.text:
Some are hooked on their drugs, but this site
Has addicted me. My tragic plight
Keeps my eyes on the screen.
Go for walks? I'm not keen
On that plan. On my life there's a blight.

limerick_list.author: timon
limerick_list.text:
'We seek to reform the whole polity:
 Our object is perfect equality!'
 When I asked, 'That implies
 We'll be all the same size?'
 They accused me of facile frivolity.

limerick_list.author: Graig Gigol
limerick_list.text:
On his birthday, King Henry the 1st,
After eating some Cajun-spiced wurst,
Said, "We thought for a 2nd
It was juicy; we reckoned
We would eat it to lower our 3st."

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
"Jeans and T-shirt?  To see that is brutal,"
Said stylishly dressed Yankee Doodle,
A dandy, "but passion
For clothing of fashion
Is what I'd call using your noodle."

limerick_list.author: hugh t.
limerick_list.text:
The libidinous Rector of Stiffkey
Was heard one day asking a biffkey:
	"What odds for a bet
	That I never will get
Defrocked just because I like niffkey?"

limerick_list.author: thaivic
limerick_list.text:
D is Latin: five hundred, half M.
DI: crime, in Great Britain, he'll stem.
Dim: the light is turned down.
Dime is ten cents (a noun).
Dimer twins are molecular (chem).

limerick_list.author: Roger Vick
limerick_list.text:
Holey leaves! It's like blunderbuss shot,
From an insect the size of a dot.
Give those feeders a scare,
And they spring through the air.
Yup, it's flea beetle damage I've got.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
The best reason I know not to smoke
Is not cancer, which might make you croak,
But the way that the taxes
Our government maxes
Ensure, before death, that you're broke.

limerick_list.author: Kevin
limerick_list.text:
When there's two things to choose from, you may
Well decide in a leisurely way.
Unless you want neither,
Your choice will be either
The one or the other, I'd say.

limerick_list.author: proof and danmcgrath
limerick_list.text:
Abduction! By whom? The solution:
Their call suggests clear attribution.
Joe was kidnapped. He's small,
Yet they said he was tall,
So the gang must be all Lilliputian.

limerick_list.author: Giorgio Coniglio
limerick_list.text:
Canadian healthcare — sublime!
You'll start clinic appointments on time,
Except when there's a hitch,
Unpredictable glitch —
Multitasking doc's late, but no crime.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Since my youth I have had a devotion
To using an ancient pink potion
To soothe itchy bits,
Such as legs, bums, and… It's
A smart choice to use calamine lotion.

limerick_list.author: Workshop
limerick_list.text:
A dating site helps me to find
A cute person who's also inclined
To acquire a mate
For a suitable date—
Though such dates can, as happens, be blind.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
That chemistry student's ignoring
This sodium borate I'm pouring.
It has got lots of boron,
And only a moron
Would claim that this borax is boring.

limerick_list.author: splendiferous
limerick_list.text:
George Airy, astronomy guy,
Said to give Airy functions a try.
You'll find that in quantum
Mechanics you'll want 'em
When y'' = xy.

limerick_list.author: Qermaq
limerick_list.text:
Accidental's a cinch to define:
It's a sharp, flat, or natural sign
That the songwriter wrote
To the left of a note
That is out of the key, but still fine.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
We have ice bags and toe tags, galore.
Need examiners (medical)? Sure!
If your morgue's small in size,
Hire one of our guys —
Check the buys at the coroner store.

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
At the moment, I'm sad to relate,
I feel fragile, not mentally great.
A disturbed frame of mind
Is possessing me, kind
Of a bleak psychological state.

limerick_list.author: Jacqui Brown
limerick_list.text:
An alienist, Dr. Bob Lyle,
Was consulted in many a trial.
He affirmed mental fitness
Of defendant and witness,
But a guy like E. T.? Not his style.

limerick_list.author: John Critten
limerick_list.text:
Do you see all this water that's rushing
Away? I can't stop it from gushing.
This sure ain't no joke;
My W.C.'s broke—
And I just cannot stop it from flushing!

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
There are places where freedom's restrained —
Speak your mind and you might be detained.
So be brave, take a stand!
But without a free hand,
When they silence you, what have you gained?

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
When we're coming undone, rapport ceases,
And disunity only increases.
Time to break up again?
I'm beside myself then.
Fragmentation means falling to pieces.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
There's a phrase from the Latin that we
Often shorten to just A.U.C.
It's a date that you say
When you want to convey
"Count from 7-5-3 B.C.E."

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
That he spoke of a girl, I had bet a
Few dollars. "I'll never regret a
Sweet lemon so tasty!"
He'd said. I was hasty.
He was speaking of Citrus limetta.

limerick_list.author: Dave Jermy
limerick_list.text:
Though he'd led since the start of the race,
I was willing to take on the chase,
So I put on a burst,
Caught him, went into first
And then kept up that punishing pace.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Those attenuated rumbles of thunder,
Like the heavens were splitting asunder,
Are weak and still distant
But dark and persistent.
The herd's become skittish—no wonder.

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
My wood looks so good on its outer:
Its edges and corners I router.
I don't care a damn for
A flat, bevelled chamfer;
I fillet (of angles, a flouter).

limerick_list.author: Kakuzan
limerick_list.text:
In the Maghreb, as shown in your atlas,
You'll discover the mountains called Atlas;
They're named for a giant
So dim and compliant
He shouldered the world: I mean Atlas.

limerick_list.author: Kevin
limerick_list.text:
You're guilty! I have to declare,
And blameworthiness is your share.
I'm sorry, dear Roger,
You're known as a dodger
Of taxes — of that I'm aware.

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
A sexologist, asked to portray
The difference 'twixt genders today,
Gave thought to the matter
Then said, "I won't flatter.
Ten minutes on average, I'd say."

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
The bitch at the bar tells you, "Mate,
My barbiturate keeps you sedate.
So you'll favor me, please,
When we score the wet T's."
(The bar bitch you rate maybe an eight.)

limerick_list.author: BobHale
limerick_list.text:
There's no reason that we need to warn a
Motorist that we have drawn a
Clamp down on speeders,
(Get cash from the bleeders!)
With cameras on every street corner.

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
Talking price means you cannot afford
That new pad that your wife has adored.
But if you've got the rent,
Tell the world what you've spent
So your status your friends can record.

limerick_list.author: Jason Talbott
limerick_list.text:
I say denominationalism
Is a mad celebration of schism.
Every group thinks they're right
So they bicker and fight.
They should all take a breath and join PRISM.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
In the sixties, we sought to declare
Our disdain for conventional hair;
And pursuing our hippiness
With typical dippiness,
Eschewed the mundane and the square.

limerick_list.author: waterrocks
limerick_list.text:
The sweetie-jars line every wall,
Holding sugar-crazed children in thrall —
They're reluctant to budge,
'Cause, from sherbet to fudge,
The confectioner's shop has it all.

limerick_list.author: Frank Luke
limerick_list.text:
You accumulate trash; that's too bad—
Your whole house is a mess, really sad.
But your stocks have behaved—
Lots of money you've saved—
You're cleaning up, fun's to be had!

limerick_list.author: hwindle
limerick_list.text:
Mrs. Smith saves all art from her child.
Under "F," finger-painting is filed.
She notes provenance, date,
And young Tim's age and weight—
Curatorial urges gone wild!

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
Rural hedgerows in Britain provide
Secure shelter for livestock, while wide
Five-bar gates made of wood
Provide access. They're good,
Even if (latches broken) they're tied.

limerick_list.author: StephenGold
limerick_list.text:
Black economies flourish when tax
Isn't paid and enforcement is lax.
Pay me cash, save the VAT,
Where's the mischief in that?
(I'll make sure that I cover our tracks.)

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
His self-concept?  A stud who is cheeky—
But he's aging, so joints have grown creaky.
He's lost most of his hair,
Yet he feels debonair.
Past his peak, so to speak, the man's freaky.

limerick_list.author: zqms
limerick_list.text:
Fair Cassandra looked over the moat
At Achilles, a fighter of note,
Not just handsome, but glamourous.
So, with an amourous
Glance, she thus gave him a gloat.

limerick_list.author: Recumbentman
limerick_list.text:
My rickety clickety clock
Has stopped ticking—it's sticking—take stock:
By the sound of the squeals
There are bats in the wheels,
A wickedly flickery flock.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
A continuant consonant keeps
Your breath moving along — the air seeps
(Maybe out of your nose);
Though constricted, it goes,
And your speech doesn't break into beeps.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
My enemy's weak, short on guts.
I'll prevail; he just postures and struts.
He can't put up a fight;
He's expugnable, right?
If he thinks he can win, then he's nuts.

limerick_list.author: Tim Alborn
limerick_list.text:
This limerick's lines are applaudable:
The cheers are resoundingly audible.
If sung to a tune
I'd be over the moon,
And the song would be surely iPodable.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"I will fix that guy's wagon but good!"
He meant me—I was dead where I stood!
When I heard that, aghast,
I departed but fast,
And would move to Nepal if I could.

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
We should think of ourselves as trustees
Of the earth, of the air, of the trees.
Biohazards hold sway
'Cause the Bush EPA
Thinks the "P" stands for "Profits". Oh, please!

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
An assassinator's someone who kills
And will seldom use poisonous pills;
He prefers the job done
With a high-powered gun
For political motives and thrills.

limerick_list.author: WordWeaver
limerick_list.text:
The larvae of book moths: a curse
Upon volumes of prose and of verse.
For many's the time
I've stopped short in mid-rhyme
'Cause the rest has been eaten or worse.

limerick_list.author: TrossL
limerick_list.text:
Writing limericks is hard—OMG!
Lines one and two rhyme, but not three.
Three and four? Yes, they should—
Hey, so far this looks good—
And it wasn't too hard, now I see.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
To actuate means "put in motion,"
Like starting this verse (I've a notion)
And pushing it on
'Til it's weary and wan
And is happy to drown in the ocean.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
A bill to assist our fair city
Passed each house, but it's now a great pity:
The Senate won't budge,
And the House bears a grudge.
They have deadlocked the conference committee!

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
Bang on cue, his rough neighbour would call,
To complain that he'd made her kids bawl.
Then she'd bang on about,
"You're a d-i-y lout!"
When he's just banging nails in his wall.

limerick_list.author: Frank Luke
limerick_list.text:
When we're born, we start life and start being,
Commence breathing and hearing and seeing.
So much more than just this—
Sigh's a sigh, kiss a kiss.
Life's a trip—lots of we-, thee-, and me-ing.

limerick_list.author: Frank Luke
limerick_list.text:
When the statement arrives, it's the an-
nualized yield that I anxiously scan.
Then I find if I've gained
Or I've lost (market waned),
Moved ahead or stayed where I began.

limerick_list.author: GaZoom
limerick_list.text:
My skin's outer stratum is fluffed,
'Cause the corneum needs to be sloughed.
Old cells from this layer
Get drier and grayer.
After shedding that dandruff, I'm buffed!

limerick_list.author: skipjordan
limerick_list.text:
The Earth, as it shares day and night,
At equinox divvies up right.
It's the first day of fall,
When our faithful old Sol
Will for half of the time provide light.

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
The galactosyltransferase way
Is the method that comes into play
To help sperm bind with eggs
Giving pregnancy legs.
It's an enzyme, the textbooks all say.

limerick_list.author: Frank Luke
limerick_list.text:
The French national anthem was set
By this Gallic musician. Let's get
Our brave tricolor out,
With a shout-out to tout
Monsieur Berlioz, praised by us yet!

limerick_list.author: Jim Vincent
limerick_list.text:
It's my paving-stone circle of bliss,
Filled with blazing hot logs — hear 'em hiss?
With Celeste by my side,
I had firepit pride . . .
Which then burned when she gave me a kiss.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
Active citizens (neighborhood watch,
Crime prevention) are really top notch.
There's another kind, though,
And they're bugging me so—
Fleas and head lice, and crabs in my crotch.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
I'm delighted to hear bagpipes play,
In their singular, happy-sad way.
It's the best music played
In most any parade;
So it's bagpipes for me, any day.

limerick_list.author: timon
limerick_list.text:
As a prof, I can prove expertise
Just by writing pure academese:
Indigestible prose —
What it means, no-one knows;
But it's got me three higher degrees.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
There's no help counting wheels on a Humber,
Or your nieces, or pieces of lumber,
From a Prince of the Church,
Or a bird on a perch—
What you need is a cardinal number.

limerick_list.author: psh
limerick_list.text:
Ever smooth, but a few termed uncouth,
Are the paintings of Mr. Demuth.
His gold figure of five
Is a still life — alive,
Celebrating that number, forsooth.

limerick_list.author: cecelia
limerick_list.text:
She felt bad — she'd been formally chided,
For her writing was often derided.
Seemed she had great potential
For "inconsequential",
So her work limped along quite lopsided.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
On my boat, I saw whales in the wild.
A harpoon then flew out; a man smiled.
He towed one to shore,
Carved a chunk, then ten more;
Turned me into a blubbering child.

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
The Doctor replaces his faces
On a semi-occasional basis.
As a Time Lord, he tries
To prevent the demise
Of the Universe (where Time and Space is).

limerick_list.author: Bluebelle
limerick_list.text:
Traditional dancing can bring
People close, as we shuffle and swing.
In a ceilidh I'll bet
That that guy you've just met
Thinks that "stripping the willow's" a fling.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
"Oh, my hoeing is going so slow!"
Whimpered Bo, who was hoeing a row,
'Til she sliced through her shoe,
And began to boohoo,
While removing the hoe from her toe.

limerick_list.author: asjchae
limerick_list.text:
In seeking good health, folks are very
Enticed by this fruit, red and merry.
To obtain healthy skin
Or feel peace from within,
People swear by the great goji berry.

limerick_list.author: Workshop
limerick_list.text:
Tsherrman-zounding, my prronownciashun
Iss telling ze vorrld frrom vich naishun
Or cowntrrie I caim,
Zo I am not to blaim
Ven I zay zumsing vrrong at zis staishun.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
At the seance, I felt a vibration.
A diaphanous, weird emanation
From my medium host
Then, at once, formed a ghost—
Thus ectoplasm's great reputation.

limerick_list.author: Michael Daws
limerick_list.text:
An erythroblast's made to give rise
To red blood cells and, due to their size,
It must pluck out and fling
Each superfluous thing —
So the nucleus meets its demise.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
She couldn't climb up to the attic,
But Grandmother now is ecstatic.
Her doctor prescribed
Medication that jibed,
When he gave her an antirheumatic.

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
Right-wing TV host/pundit Glenn Beck
(Liberals claim he has just half a deck)
Holds his viewers in thrall
As he chalkboards it all.
Breaking news? Brilliant views? Nah, just dreck.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
"The arroyo's our place to lie low:
Thicket's thick there, so nothing would show,
It's so brambly and brushed,
And the atmosphere hushed…"
"If that's so, we could die there. Who'd know?"

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
A chibbal's a lot like a chive.
It's an herb with a taste that's alive.
It can help any dish,
Whether salad or fish;
For the bland, it adds dandy new drive.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
"I'm the worst kind of bad desperado;
'Show mercy to none' is my motto!"
As this sentence was said,
He was shot full of lead
By some dudes who ignored his bravado.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
I'm an actor!  No job could be greater!
And fame will come, sooner or later.
I would die for my art!
And my most recent part?
I'm appearing in Schrafft's (as a waiter).

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
With a double entendre, life's sunny
Through a two-meaning phrase, often punny.
Skilful wordplay will whizz
Up your limericks with fizz—
And makes many indecently funny.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
My mortgage, adjustable rate,
Linked to indices (health of the state),
Shows there once was a time
When the lending was prime.
Now I watch as my assets deflate.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
A wombat's odd feces have faces —
Not with eyes, but six sides in all cases.
Neither pellets nor tubes,
But hard, stackable cubes
Are produced: Nose-high signs in most places.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
You can stretch a poetical line, (silent beat)
And your anapests still come out fine. (silent beat)
Standard limericks append
Silent beats at the end
Of lines 1, 2, and 5, just like mine. (silent beat)

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
If your secretary isn't resistant
To "working" while partners are distant,
It's certainly vital
To grant her a title
That's finer: viz., Admin. Assistant.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
These eye-drops you'll find cycloplegic.
The reason they're given? Strategic:
Your doc is desirous
Of a dilated  iris.
(It will slow your work bibliopegic.)

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Clara Bow, as she puts on her sweater,
Purrs softly, "I've never had better."
'Round my finger she's curled
In my fantasy world.
(In real life? No, I never have met her.)

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
With respect from our club my incentive,
My system for filing's inventive.
I keep every last note,
Every word, every quote.
You could say that I'm annals-retentive.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
An owl, who was gloomy and stygian,
Swerved, avoiding a flighty young pigeon,
But lamented, with pique,
That she'd dented her beak
While preventing that two-bird colligeon.

limerick_list.author: Mad Kane
limerick_list.text:
My writing is great, you should know,
Yet you turn it all down.  What a blow!
Your taste is awry,
Else you surely would buy
My submissions.  I'm through.  Keep your dough!

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
What's electoral? Any connection
Or allusion to any election,
Like the voters' cross section,
Or the outcome projection,
Or the poll-watchers' loyal protection.

limerick_list.author: Giorgio Coniglio
limerick_list.text:
My heretical view: Seems to me
It's grotesque, just a bad rêverie.
Errant knight, lance down, caught
In a faery child's 'grot',
In John Keats'  "La Belle Dame Sans Merci".

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
If a man had a manual choke
Like some cars, he'd be slow to go broke.
Pull a knob, and behold!
He could flood in more gold —
But less oxygen might make him croak.

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
With a ligature, write anapæst —
Or at least make it -paest — in the East.
Those folks in the West
Mostly write anapest:
A bone of contention? — A feast!

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Frank played football, the source of his woes:
Fractured spine, twisted knee, broken nose.
Now he's E-D-D-U,
But that's all he can do.
He's not ready just yet for the pros.

limerick_list.author: Graham Lester
limerick_list.text:
There's a tune that is certain to please at
Any place you can tinkle the keys at;
So many a showman
Thanks Euday L. Bowman
For a rag that is nothing to sneeze at.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
A professor once wrote in his journal:
"I've the secret of life eviternal.
Don't expect my demise.
You'll receive a surprise:
I stay youthful and vigorous, vernal."

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
Bring it on!  We will never be cowed.
We'll stay standing resilient and proud.
Are we up for a fight
Against evil?  Damn right!
Terror simply will not be allowed.

limerick_list.author: skipjordan
limerick_list.text:
A new pop-up has got me up upset:
Said, "Ms. Garr, it is you I will get!
Quite soon you will face me
With no way to trace me.
I'm on darknet — and coming, my pet."

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
Firstborn Johnny's the one she loves best,
Head and shoulders above all the rest.
He's her favourite son,
The most cherished — the one
That she'll never throw out of the nest.

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
I expect an expectorant will
Clear the phlegm from my lungs, help it spill
Up and into my mouth
Till I spit it down south.
Guess just how many buckets I'll fill...!

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
I'm reluctant to make this admission
But it's true, I'm no academician.
Still, who needs degrees
To write limericks like these?
I've got chutzpah and brains and ambition!

limerick_list.author: Frank Luke
limerick_list.text:
A small tab of some acid, a quick
Flight, a trip into space—what a kick!
I'm so zonked, really flying,
Out-of-sight, in-the-skying!
Hell or heaven, can't say—take your pick.

limerick_list.author: Son of Baltimore
limerick_list.text:
She prays, with her head hanging down,
"Lord, send us a biblical noun."
Then her Bible she cracks,
And it opens to Acts.
Now it's Festus we're calling our town.

limerick_list.author: Mary
limerick_list.text:
The versatile cotton plant's seed
Can be used to meet many a need:
To grow cotton, of course,
And it's also a source
Both of oil and of animal feed.

limerick_list.author: a.groovymind
limerick_list.text:
The Koran says: an eye for an eye,
And believers all chorus aye aye.
Such barbaric old laws
Ought to stick in their craws —
I can only lament ai-yi-yi!

limerick_list.author: Michael Daws
limerick_list.text:
Cytoskeletons obviate muddle,
Allowing a kick or a cuddle.
Their fibers, like spells,
Hold together our cells —
Without them we'd just be a puddle.

limerick_list.author: Scott Campisi
limerick_list.text:
Two parts silicon. Oxygen six.
That makes silicate, which we can mix
With aluminum; throw
In potassium. So
We make amphigene (leucite) for kicks.

limerick_list.author: agingjb
limerick_list.text:
That obscurest of laureates, Cibber
Was mocked by A. Pope (the great ribber).
He was rude; he was vain,
And a bit of a pain;
And his verses, Pope said, were just gibber.

limerick_list.author: Bluebelle
limerick_list.text:
When on trial in a court, I'd have thought
You can't legally buy or be bought,
But Nick's bribed half the jury,
Inciting some fury,
Which doubles his troubles—he's caught.

limerick_list.author: Mary
limerick_list.text:
Nutted corn flakes, bananaed her pie,
Gravied biscuits without  saying why.
As a cook she's reclusive,
Inventing intrusive
New verbs for her dishes—so sly.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
On my rose bush, a brace of convergents
Are fighting an aphid resurgence.
As these ladybugs feed,
They are just what I need
For American Beauty's emergence.

limerick_list.author: AndrewB
limerick_list.text:
There are ATCs helping you fly
Since a very large airport is nigh.
All those folks on the ground
Will help move you around
When you're in controlled airspace, up high.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Docudrama, a term categorical,
Suits a play with pretensions historical.
Thus the late Syngman Rhee
Might be seen on TV
In a bio, that's—well—metaphorical.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
In voting, a long time ago,
A black ball implied "anti", not "pro";
So you blackball (reject
From a group or a sect)
When you ostracize someone you know.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
The Tooth Fairy's gang's gotten scary,
In attacking the zonked and unwary.
Being thorough and ruthless,
They're leaving 'em toothless,
As advised by their two consiglieri.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
When you're out very early, it's true,
You'll see dawn. To stay dry, here's a clue:
Wear your boots (don't complain)—
Though there hasn't been rain,
All the grass will be covered in dew.

limerick_list.author: Mr E S
limerick_list.text:
In what language does that choir sing?
Are those Russian or Serb tones that ring?
Well, no matter the tonic,
It's still Church Slavonic—
To Orthodox priests the real thing.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
If it bites, it is something that's bad,
Such as losing an i- (Phone or Pad),
Or a fraudulent deal
That was far from a steal
And discovering one has been had.

limerick_list.author: Chaiwallah
limerick_list.text:
If I call you a basket, be sure
That my anger is like to endure;
As with malice and spite
I will take great delight
In implying your birth was impure.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
Old Albert's incredibly nice,
And his gods never seem to play dice,
But with hickory dickory
Point-of-view trickery,
Clocks run down relative mice.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
The em dash — the em dash — don't yell!
Overused?  Maybe so — I can't tell.
The surprise punctuation
Provokes condemnation —
Too much? —  I don't care — what the hell.

limerick_list.author: bob killian
limerick_list.text:
The fault with the room that I took,
In the cheapest hotel I could book?
"Hello, front desk? I think —
Got a leak in my sink."
"Go ahead," he said, "no one will look."

limerick_list.author: Lanny
limerick_list.text:
At our limericks, readers might bridle
With enmity anapesticidal.
Brilliant puns, it now seems,
Merely clutter their dreams
While they doze through American Idol.

limerick_list.author: Doug Aldridge
limerick_list.text:
The arrivers are those who appear
On the scene to a great joyous cheer.
Whether early or late
To a great party date,
Let the fun now begin...they are here!

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
With your wrists tied, your arms have been passed
O'er your knees, which are bent, then held fast
By a pole through the hole
'Tween your limbs for control.
You've been bucked by the guards that you sassed.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
A worker at French's got flustered
When the boss at his work station blustered,
"You gotta dilute
The Dijon—don't get cute.
You'll be canned if you can't cut the mustard!"

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
If winning the war's your objective,
You'll follow this crucial directive
For the arms you procure —
Ships, planes, guns — best make sure
That your enginery's very effective.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Can a nightmare at times be an omen?
Ask Shakespeare's unfortunate Roman.
Did his wife's dream foretoken
His death? She had spoken,
But daggers rent Caesar's abdomen.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"Oh, you think you're so smart," shouted Erica,
"With command of arcane esoterica!
Can you back up that claim?
OK, jerk, try to name
The Confederate States of America."

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
The contrabassoonist was lax,
And the sax player missed a few tracks,
But the very worst tone
Came from notes that were blown
By the oboist—stridulous couacs.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
"I emplead," Lena screeched. "I accuse
That big brute who inflicted this bruise!
If this lawcourt does right,
It will choose to indict
That foul boozer who loves to abuse."

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
Know the pose where the cobra arose?
Lift your chest from the ground; point your toes.
With each breath that you take,
Arch your back like a snake
Poised to strike—bhujangasana pose!

limerick_list.author: Jesse Frankovich
limerick_list.text:
Morning drivers, beware of the fog;
Midnight prowlers, beware of the dog.
And tourists, I'll warn ya:
In south California,
Take caution—beware of the smog.

limerick_list.author: Snowy Owl
limerick_list.text:
I would sure like to trade in the scamp
Who is serving as my aide-de-camp.
He won't polish my boots,
And he never salutes, . . .
But the General's brother's his gramp.

limerick_list.author: Steve Andersen
limerick_list.text:
By her suitor the woman was charmed,
But was fearful the man might be armed.
Was he totin' a gun,
Or just lookin' for fun?
Should this girl be aroused or alarmed?

limerick_list.author: sigg
limerick_list.text:
The new version was not up to par
'Cause the cuts made the story bizarre.
Too much plot was removed,
So it's easily proved
'Twas a case of abridgement too far.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
All your life, you keep getting away with it:
Flaunt your mountain of money, and play with it.
You've beguiled and seduced;
Now it's come home to roost
And the press will be making you pay with it.

limerick_list.author: skipjordan and JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
There is an old biker named Lance,
Who keeps on surprising in France,
Where the drug tests again
And again are in vain,
'Cause he's clean (which they knew in advance).

limerick_list.author: Basingstoke
limerick_list.text:
My home is exquisitely clean,
My kids well-behaved and serene.
I'm attractive and healthy,
Successful and wealthy
As I fantasize...hey, I'm a queen!

limerick_list.author: Jane Auerbach
limerick_list.text:
Miss Piggy, to Kermit: "We're through.
Remember, it's me; it's not you.
But that boar with the Benz
Has become . . . more than friends.
So, Green Fella, not much you can do."

limerick_list.author: PGS
limerick_list.text:
You address someone unknown by email
As "Dear sir", and expect "him" to remail?
A girl, so addressed,
Might feel injured or stressed
And call such a mistake antifemale!

limerick_list.author: jojo
limerick_list.text:
A sweet apple pie with molasses—
Ambrosia, beloved by the masses.
So it is when Miss Gowdy
Makes apple pandowdy
For kids in her cookery classes.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Days are tiresome at Oshkosh, by gosh;
In my by-times I cultivate squash.
Our division does snow plows
All year, so I know plows…
And squash. Neither asks much panache.

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
Thick and wrinkled, a pachyderm's derm
Is its skin. Whether flimsy or firm,
Be it smooth, be it creased
(Mainly used of a beast),
We've not ceased to prolong this short term.

limerick_list.author: Ruchiccio
limerick_list.text:
There once was pop-guzzling gent
Who learned what embrittlement meant
After all his teeth broke
From the acid of Coke.
They got weaker... and weaker... and went.

limerick_list.author: Dr. Work
limerick_list.text:
Walter Brown, Jimmy Rushing, Big Joe,
Eddie "Cleanhead" (hoo, boy, could he blow!)...
They were blues shouters all
Who could fill the whole hall
With their voices (no amps!) for the show.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
Watching Plumber Heat: Valves on the Blink —
Dubbed in English from Swedish, I think —
All the sound added after
Made lust turn to laughter:
The dialogue seemed out of synch.

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
My doc says I'm right on the border
Of a crippling anxiety disorder.
A high maintenance girl
Has my heart in a whirl,
But I fear that I just can't afford her.

limerick_list.author: James Dobson
limerick_list.text:
My soccer team boasts a back four.
That's a sporting, defense-minded corps:
In a line, this quartet
Tries to counter each threat
And so not let the other side score.

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
When you're facing a grim vigilante,
And your chance of escaping seems scanty,
You'd be happy to pay
For a do-over play —
Start anew from the status quo ante.

limerick_list.author: Bob Egg
limerick_list.text:
I'm a gentleman, suave, well-to-do;
On my promises I'll follow through.
So don't think it absurd
When I keep to my word
And pen verse about pee-pee and poo.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Epitomizer: one who abstracts
The essence of volumes or tracts.
Though authors may pout
At their good stuff left out,
It's just "No sir, no nuance. Just facts."

limerick_list.author: Mary
limerick_list.text:
This submarine landscape extends
Out from continents. Then it descends
To the deep ocean floor.
There is much to explore
In its shallows, for many good ends.

limerick_list.author: VERaLOE
limerick_list.text:
Too short's your electrical lead?
That's unlucky, I freely concede.
I might as well mention,
It is an extension
Type cable connection you need.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
It must nourish, and must be digestible
(Whether tasty or wholly detestable);
The food that we eat
For a meal or a treat:
Each item is called a comestible.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
Many cost factors go in the mix—
Raw material (mortar and bricks),
Direct labor, and all—
For the city's new mall,
But they've left out the booze and the chicks!

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
An aigulet strengthens the tip
Of a shoelace. This plasticky strip
Can get crushed with each stride
If your sneakers aren't tied,
Which today makes a teenager hip.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
Your duncery shows every day,
'Cause your brain's just a useless puree.
You're a nincompoop, fool,
And you flunked out of school.
No one's home underneath your toupee.

limerick_list.author: Jane Auerbach
limerick_list.text:
Arame (that's seaweed, to you)
Can be stir-fried to feed a whole crew.
As a side dish with fish,
Some will say it's delish,
But tonight I'd prefer a fondue.

limerick_list.author: AndrewB
limerick_list.text:
My poor rug is all covered in grime
And irregular patches of slime.
I'll buy carpet shampoo,
Rent a RugDoctor, too.
A clean carpet takes work and some time.

limerick_list.author: Errol Nimbly
limerick_list.text:
I hear Canada's covered in snow,
That it's freezing and nothing will grow.
They catch fish through the ice,
Hunt for berries and mice...
Planned a trip, but I don't think I'll go.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Embryogenesis, scientists say
Is how zygotes begin, and the way
That an embryo grows.
(Although everyone knows
That the pre-start's the fun part.  So stay!)

limerick_list.author: R. A. Shortfellow
limerick_list.text:
For those nose clamps that calm a wild horse,
Or some spectacles (English, of course),
Or in torture, cruel tools,
Or for close clingy fools,
The word barnacles I would endorse.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Take a trip in a bus or a car,
And before you have gotten too far,
A comfort stop's what
You will not have forgot.
You will need one, whoever you are.

limerick_list.author: Melissa Balmain
limerick_list.text:
Years ago, kids could all understand
That extreme meant "intense, out of hand."
But today, how'd they know?
When each sport, snack and show
Is "extreme," they must think it means "bland."

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
As a person in perfect control
Of my future, through goal after goal,
Their attainment I slate
For a far-distant date
(When I hope to be out on parole).

limerick_list.author: Jason Talbott
limerick_list.text:
Your car is a complex machine.
Your engine and tranny convene
To help spin your wheels.
Something's missing it feels...
It's the driveline, the piece in between.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
At the fresh Balfour cheese I would gawk.
'Bout its sweet nutty flavor, I'd talk.
It's both crumbly and hard,
Held in highest regard
In N.Z. Disagree? Take a walk!

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Got my bar, Mom; that means I'm commissioned—
Bought my Class A's; my gear's requisitioned.
I'm an officer now,
Though I'm not sure quite how:
Made lieutenant, and never auditioned.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
My dad's searching for words brings such pain.
We expect, it's increasingly plain,
As clear thoughts lag behind
And bedimmed grows his mind,
A near-total eclipse of the brain.

limerick_list.author: art bates
limerick_list.text:
An old bookkeeper died in the night.
So the staff sprung his drawer for a sight
Of what mystery lay
Where he'd looked every day;
'Twas a note: "debit: left, credit: right".

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
Empty words in abundant supply—
It's the mantra you hear when you fly.
Disembarking the plane,
There it goes, once again:
It's "buh-bye" and "buh-bye" and "buh-bye".

limerick_list.author: PGS
limerick_list.text:
Frankish kings, ruling Gallo-Germanic
Parts of Europe, were somewhat tyrannic;
More than old Merovingians,
These Carolingians
Kept the old Saxons in panic.

limerick_list.author: Richard English
limerick_list.text:
The lexical sign ampersand
(A corruption of "and per se and"),
Though very inviting
In casual writing,
In formal should always be banned.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Many teens wear their pants way too low
And present a gross "butt cleavage" show.
Let's crack down (pun intended)
On this style till it's ended
(Though not picking on Jill—only Joe).

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
A fascinating woman, Adele;
I'm enchanted and under her spell.
My attention she's captured,
I'm rapt and enraptured,
Perhaps I'm in love — can you tell?

limerick_list.author: neilski
limerick_list.text:
Once a bus route went straight past my door.
It ran three times a day; but no more,
Since the V28
(Being constantly late)
Was replaced by the 74.

limerick_list.author: sallycello
limerick_list.text:
An insect who's much too gregarious,
Is the bedbug, Cimex lectularius.
This miserable pest
Your bed will infest;
He's a bad bug, his mission nefarious.

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
So he meets with a shifty young guy
Who says, "Man, wanna give this a try?
It's some powerful stuff!"
He agrees, "Strong enough...
But your asking price, man, is too high."

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
My dad dates a woman who's childish.
Her temperament's sweetish and mildish.
Though he sometimes complains
When she wears Mary Janes,
He prefers her to gals that are wildish.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
The Limerick Co. veep
Said, "We're bankrupt.  And debt? We're in deep!
Partners stole what we earned
So the lesson I've learned:
Be aware of the co. you keep."

limerick_list.author: AndrewB
limerick_list.text:
When a spiffy new weapon of war
Was the flintlock, a fusilier corps
Was assigned this new gear.
Now the name is still here,
But they don't use those guns any more.

limerick_list.author: PGS
limerick_list.text:
It's surrounded by beautiful beaches,
And a look on the map quickly teaches:
This sea's not a menace
From Corfu to Venice,
Where its largest diameter reaches.

limerick_list.author: bob killian
limerick_list.text:
Doing "honeydew" jobs, every weenie'll
Complain that such work makes him menial,
But I check off each chore,
Smiling, asking for more:
Masochistic, or merely congenial?

limerick_list.author: psh
limerick_list.text:
"We don't need stinkin' badgers," he said,
See, his zoo has no room — and it bred
Ferret-badgers before.
Keepers roundly deplore
The malodorous aura they spread.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
"Education's a great cornucopia;
A degree is the key to utopia!"
(All I got from those crooks
As I pored over books
Was a case of acute asthenopia.)

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Razing towers, we never get bored.
Imprecision we just can't afford;
Our explosions will stink
If they're not quite in sync,
So I think we'll use detonating cord.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Your tardiness happens a lot.
Excusable? No, it is not!
My attitude's hardened,
Forget being pardoned —
You're fired right now, on the spot!

limerick_list.author: GalFisk
limerick_list.text:
What is cesium-137?
Radiation turned up to 11.
This bomb or reactor
Contaminant factor
Can kill you and send you to heaven.

limerick_list.author: pöt
limerick_list.text:
Church pew: Here I sit during mass.
As it's wooden, it's hard on my ass.
So I won't be found snoring,
Though the preacher is boring,
And the sermon he offers is crass.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The calcarine fissure is where
Lies your visual cortex (a pair—
One the left; one the right).
It's the site of your sight—
So neurology textbooks declare.

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
When a woman shows traits of a man,
And her hormones are normal, this can
Be a complex that's named
For Diana, the famed
Roman goddess who hunted with Pan.

limerick_list.author: Dave Jermy
limerick_list.text:
Can you count the dismissals in cricket?
Bowled or caught, leg before or hit wicket,
Timed or run out, retired,
Hit it twice, stumps expired,
Block the field. Got all ten? Then I'll tick it!

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
His experimentation's controlled,
But alchemically clever and bold.
Taking tungsten and lead,
He's been forging ahead
Turning commonplace metals to gold.

limerick_list.author: J. E. Pettit
limerick_list.text:
Letter 'A' said, "I find it absurd
This illogical insult's occurred.
I'm more frequently used,
So I'm truly confused:
Why does 'Z' always get the last word?"

limerick_list.author: Frank Luke and Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
When a job seems unpleasant or hard,
Such as cleaning the closets or yard,
Grip the prob and just pull it.
C'mon, bite the bullet—
And shake from your ass all that lard.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Docs in ASAM all treat the affliction
That's known to the world as addiction.
They'll help any youth
To tell falsehood from truth—
There are no harmless drugs; that's a fiction!

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
As a weaver of cloth, I assume
That you work on a specialized loom.
You amaze me with patterns
Of stars, Earths and Saturns.
Is a drawloom back there in your room?

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Dad screamed, "Moron, you've got us off course!" fully
Mindful that speaking so forcefully
Crushed youthful pride.
Since we'd both nearly died,
Father spoke with harsh strength, unremorsefully.

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
Eaten food that's gone off?  Then I fear
That abdominal  cramps may be near.
There's not much you can do
Except—quick, find a loo,
If you find you've acute diarrhoea.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Clearly, Dr. James Barry gained fame
As a surgeon. His times were to blame
For the secret he hid.
Want to know what he did?
Here's a hint: Margaret Ann was his name.

limerick_list.author: StephenGold
limerick_list.text:
A celebrated new-age musician,
Renowned for expressive rendition,
His air barely started,
Prodigiously farted.
There followed a long intermission.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
You've been schooled; has it all been for naught?
Guess you're not yet prepared as we thought.
Don't just stand half asleep;
Meet a lady, bow deep:
Drag your foot, as a gentleman ought.

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
If the climate you're in's continental,
Then the temperature's not temperamental
Day by day, but by season:
Summer broils; winter's freezin' —
A maritime climate's more gentle.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
It's a layer of stuff in the brain.
It's a sketch that's designed to explain.
It's a pressurized place
For explorers of space.
Now for me, no more capsules remain.

limerick_list.author: Dave Jermy
limerick_list.text:
Do you want the whole crowd to adore
Your technique as you're looking to score?
If so, what you should strive
For's a sumptuous drive:
You'll look great while the ball runs for four.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
A catcall's a rude sort of call
That, at ball games, could touch off a brawl.
But: "Here Puss, Puss, Puss, Puss,
Puss, Puss, Puss, Puss, Puss, Puss,
Puss, Puss, Puss!"?  No, not that at all.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
This asthenia's making me mild
(I am weak, with the strength of a child).
Now let's guess at the reasons:
I've too many seasons?
Or maybe my lover just smiled!

limerick_list.author: Benton Randall Olmsted
limerick_list.text:
Too much sediment causes the beds
Of streams to aggrade as it spreads.
This may spoil the wishes
Of some of the fishes
If streams cannot cover their heads.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
For those who are long in the tooth
And are seeking a fountain of youth:
In your search for perfection,
Try Botox injection.
It won't be considered uncouth.

limerick_list.author: Jim Vincent
limerick_list.text:
To determine Earth's shape and its size,
And find points 'neath its beautiful skies,
There's a branch of applied
Mathematics I tried:
It's geodesy. (Now I feel wise.)

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
This self-referent lim's denotatum
Could well cause me to post an erratum.
Like potato / potato,
Tomato / tomato,
Each one is a jinx, and I hate 'em.

limerick_list.author: Jim Vincent
limerick_list.text:
Precious fabric was dropped by that hag
As it slipped from the top of her bag:
It's a keepsake for her
Of a memory, a blur,
But for us, a discardable rag.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Things do alter, transform—understood.
As a rule, we adapt (knock on wood).
Changing clocks, changing weather,
Can't we all pull together
And settle some place that's just good?

limerick_list.author: David Schildkret and Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
An acquittal implies we acquit,
Though another noun once was legit.
I doubt OJ'd have walked
If Cochran had squawked,
"Vote acquitment: the glove doesn't fit!"

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
A porter's not paid what he's worth;
For a tip, he'll move heaven and earth.
Tough to sleep on a train?
Pullman bunks are a pain—
Pay the man; he'll procure a new berth.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
She's a hellcat of fame down in Natchez;
Caught on radar, they batten the hatches.
"Wrecked my eyes," one bewails.
"Check the size of her nails.
I got clapperclawed; look at the scratches."

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
Sue's abdominal area was bloated,
So the docs tried ballottement.  They voted?
No, they prodded and poked,
And the action provoked
Susie's organs to bob, since they floated.

limerick_list.author: David
limerick_list.text:
A foot is most commonly found
At the end of each leg of a hound.
If by chance one is not
Found attached to that spot,
It will still be quite close to the ground.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
I've got nerve for observing neurectomies
And the balls to watch all orchiectomies.
There are times, though, I won't
Be so gutsy.  I don't
Have the stomach for viewing gastrectomies.

limerick_list.author: bestswanbird
limerick_list.text:
Underpaid, overworked, heart of gold,
Food to cook, house to clean, clothes to fold.
She's a carer, that's all,
But she answers their call.
Loves her job looking after the old.

limerick_list.author: Roger Vick
limerick_list.text:
"What do quarter and nail and an ell
Have in common?" "I'm stumped, please do tell."
"All were measures of cloth,
But today merely froth:
Now redundant, so, sadly, farewell."

limerick_list.author: Paperdragon
limerick_list.text:
In the silence I heard myself say,
"We will not be ad-libbing today.
Angel Gabriel, please,
Will you stop saying 'Jeez'?
It's an effing nativity play!"

limerick_list.author: John Young
limerick_list.text:
As the hub of my showroom, my store court,
Is simply too small, I need more court.
For a chance to compete
With the used-car elite,
I need space for more cars on my forecourt.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
I fell, skinned my knee, and gee whiz,
It sure hurts. Mommy kissed it, then riz,
Saying, "There you go, John —
Your gonalgia's all gone."
Well, it's not, but she thinks that it is.

limerick_list.author: Dr. Work
limerick_list.text:
A gasworks was used to turn coal
Into gases that light up your stroll,
Since the town gas, at night,
Kept the street lamps alight
(If the lighter came by with his pole).

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The accumbens sits deep in your brain
And lights up when there's pleasure (not pain).
If a drug makes it glow
Once too often, you know,
You may crave it again and again.

limerick_list.author: BobHale
limerick_list.text:
You say you're at my "beck and call".
You will do what I say, big or small.
I say, "What the heck
Do we mean by a beck?"
It's a nod or a gesture, that's all.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
In a nest to which Mom's unattached,
A brood parasite's own egg is hatched.
There it's raised by another
Egg's dutiful mother
After sometimes her own are dispatched.

limerick_list.author: danmcgrath
limerick_list.text:
In the market, it's utter simplicity:
Lower price, and with near synchronicity,
The demand will increase!
But how much, piece by piece,
Is the heart of demand elasticity.

limerick_list.author: Jenn Phillips
limerick_list.text:
Microscopic green algae, akin
To the flagellate stoneworts, have been
Picked apart to the gene:
Haploids blobby in mien
Echo land plants' langsyne deep within.

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
Give to radical, fair attribution?
Maybe this: Social change / revolution.
But a radical, see,
When described here as "free"
Has potential for body pollution.

limerick_list.author: David Schildkret
limerick_list.text:
Accepting house:  place where you go
To turn bills of exchange into dough—
Not the place I was born,
Where they treat me with scorn,
And my confidence tanks at "hello."

limerick_list.author: Type A
limerick_list.text:
In psychology courses you'll learn
In the anal stage two-year olds yearn
To glean joy from their bums.
It's not smutty; that comes
When the genital stage takes its turn.

limerick_list.author: danmcgrath
limerick_list.text:
In Alice's afternoon dreams
(And so slickly in Grace's, it seems),
Lives the Dormouse who's sleepy,
Whose comments seem creepy
Since treacle and drugs are his themes.

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
Soon the five became six (for a year),
And their leaders, with stealth and good cheer,
In a castle in France
Sought world trade to advance;
For recession was something to fear.

limerick_list.author: MattMonitto
limerick_list.text:
This nightclub's the hottest in town!
Not a person is sporting a frown.
And they're up to the times
When it comes to rap rhymes;
When the DJ gets "Down," they get down.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
Every time we go walking, he'll pee
On some hydrants and many a tree.
So wherever we roam,
He will know the way home
By his calling card.  "Dad, follow me!"

limerick_list.author: Pie Snelson
limerick_list.text:
I gossiped but don't be offended.
Your tagged, naked butt looked—um—splendid?
I'm sorry 'bout Facebook.
Oh, don't cite the casebook.
You're suing?  And now I'm defriended?

limerick_list.author: StephenGold
limerick_list.text:
We're drug traffickers. What do you need?
We have smack and superior weed
You can sell on the street
To the nice folks you meet.
That's our mission—each day a good deed.

limerick_list.author: Dottie
limerick_list.text:
The accent of Digorie Phelps—
So far back! Meaning scalps, he says 'skelps'.
His collection has rets'
Hair, and hemsters' and bets'.
(You don't have to be mad, but it helps.)

limerick_list.author: Dr. Work
limerick_list.text:
Whenever my son's with a date,
I stay on their tail (which they hate!).
They think that I'm vile,
Since I'm cramping their style,
But not once have they stayed out too late.

limerick_list.author: skipjordan
limerick_list.text:
A plumber (and poet) was flirtin'
With censorship (very uncertain).
So he flushed the foul word
(In this case, it was turd)
To avoid being blocked by the "Curtain."

limerick_list.author: Ruchiccio
limerick_list.text:
Periodically, scientists see
A new element (e.g. Np)
That they cannot break down.
Since I boast great renown,
Maybe one will be named after me!

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
Your admirableness served to enlighten
My castaway crowd, but you frighten
Them now. So, the twist:
