I'm afraid you're dismissed
(With an excellent reference), Crichton.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
I'm a birler whose skill is supreme,
Treading logs for America's team.
Though the logs bob and spin,
I just never fall in —
Help! I'm trapped in a lumberjack's dream!

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
My tummy felt terrible when
I ate one dozen eggs con Cayenne.
With digestion so dismal,
I took Pepto-Bismol,
Which made me eupeptic again.

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
If yours is the singular dream
To question the things that don't seem
So well understood,
Just pull on your hood
And head for the fair Academe.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Count to ten, Monique. Give it a try,
Then we'll zoom in real close on your eye.
Next a nuclear blast
Will leave viewers aghast:
"Vote for Johnson or else we'll all die!"

limerick_list.author: Roger Dunn
limerick_list.text:
I can sense that my birth's drawing near!
Water breaks! I'm about to appear!
It's a time to rejoice!
What's that sound? It's a voice!
"Look! A girl! You've a daughter! She's here!"

limerick_list.author: Jacqui Brown
limerick_list.text:
Each year towards the end of November,
A calendar meant for December
Appeared on the  wall
Of my family's front hall—
It's something I'll always remember.

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
With her C's and her U's and her T's,
Young Olivia's strokes always please.
Yes, her hand is grand; but
Should such writing be cut?
It's the site of a breach of the P's.

limerick_list.author: Bluebelle
limerick_list.text:
My dear little cat lives indoors
And has claws at the ends of his paws,
While a pun that's the worst
Says a comma's reversed—
It's a pause at the end of a clause!

limerick_list.author: Ruchiccio
limerick_list.text:
A seismologist once fooled around
And uncovered some data profound
About earthquaves. When tested,
The findings suggested
Her theory's on real shaky ground.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
An albatross over the sail
Betokens impending travail.
The source of this word
Is a seafaring bird,
The alcatraz, just like the jail.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
The Cadets' "Don't Be Angry" first landed
Then "Why Don't You Write Me?" but branded
The Jacks—a slight cheat
So they wouldn't compete.
In the jungle, they later got stranded.

limerick_list.author: PGS and Tim Alborn
limerick_list.text:
On the walls of the faculty club,
Bougainvillea, colorful shrub,
Boasts of bracts that enthrall,
But has flowers so small;
There's the rub. Of this shrub, that's the nub.

limerick_list.author: Frank Luke
limerick_list.text:
When events leave you wanting to bawl,
The result's an expression of gall:
Fierce anger, a storm,
Gathers force and takes form,
And its outburst can cast a black pall.

limerick_list.author: BobHale
limerick_list.text:
"What a wonderful town's Hay-on-Wye!"
Said the bibliophile, with a sigh.
"All those crannies and nooks
Filled with nothing but books!
I could browse through the shelves till I die."

limerick_list.author: David
limerick_list.text:
Though on Skye are two hills with soft crests
Which entice men on magical quests,
Further south they can dally
In Skye's fertile valley,
So don't remain long on her breasts.

limerick_list.author: Jim Vincent
limerick_list.text:
While you're stitching my thumb, Doc, please know
Latin's handy, but filum must go.
Though its origin's "thread",
It is best left unsaid:
It is not an apt term when you sew.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
An Evangelist once turned up dead
In a region of China gone Red.
Robert Welch formed a troop:
Ultra-right-wing, this group;
Anti-Red are the Birchers.  Nuff said.

limerick_list.author: a.groovymind
limerick_list.text:
Superstition's got hold of you, honey,
If you carry the paw of a bunny.
You think that it's lucky?
Well, think again, ducky.
It's really a foot fetish — funny!

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Some companies carried out fudging;
Their profit and loss sheets showed smudging.
When the SEC looked,
And found books had been cooked,
CEOs went to court for adjudging.

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
Some ambitions of mine are to share
In the profits from rents in Times Square,
Then to end work at noon,
And to walk on the moon.
Are these castles of mine in the air?

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
A colonial un-guided missile
Was a rider named Israel Bissell,
Who yelled like Revere,
"The damn redcoats are near!"
His accomplishment makes some folks bristle.

limerick_list.author: Jacqui Brown
limerick_list.text:
"I dare you," Athena once said,
"To win at the loom. Go ahead."
Arachne defied her—
And soon was a spider
Left hanging by one silken thread.

limerick_list.author: Jeff Foster
limerick_list.text:
A marooned mountaineer in hot tights
Desultorily spent her cold nights
Till she lured smitten Sherpas
With a surplus of purpose
To guide her along to new heights.

limerick_list.author: Doug Harris
limerick_list.text:
Betweentimes is sort of betwixt
The present in which we're now fixed
And the future that's due.
(I hear tell Doctor Who
Is in trouble for getting them mixed.)

limerick_list.author: GalFisk
limerick_list.text:
Signs of neon and light tubes (fluorescent)
Show a glow discharge (not incandescent).
Electrons will pass,
Strike and ionize gas,
With a glow either mild or incessant.

limerick_list.author: bestswanbird
limerick_list.text:
If you're climbing up high and you fall,
Landing hard on your heel not the ball
Of your foot, it may make
Your calcaneus break:
First you'll sprawl, then you'll bawl as you crawl.

limerick_list.author: Carol June Hooker
limerick_list.text:
Coarse-grained bread, torn and cursed, came to be
A medieval guilt/innocence key.
The accused, at a table,
Heard, "Eat if you're able.
If you swallow the corsned, go free."

limerick_list.author: R. A. Shortfellow
limerick_list.text:
An ecu's a coin from old France
Worth three livres (for those in finance).
At first it was gold,
And then silver. Just sold
My whole stash — had to fix up my manse.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
There's a lock in the knob of your door.
It's a stock type of lock, nothing more.
A key with its ridges
Moves pins a few smidges,
And spins the cylindrical core.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
The Deep South, where plantations were great:
The Magnolia, the Pelican State,
Yellowhammer and Peach
And Palmetto. And each,
What with cracklins, has problems with weight.

limerick_list.author: John Wellington Wells
limerick_list.text:
Up in heaven it's white as the snow,
And the weather is hot down below.
While my choice (though I ski)
Is not one of degree,
Still your offer of wealth I'll forgo.

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
Said the priest, "Once I've searched all the floors
I'll discover the home of the whores.
I shall pray I get in,
And then cleanse it of sin.
God is Love—and my faith opens doors."

limerick_list.author: Chaiwallah
limerick_list.text:
The people one meets when one shoots!
Like the Major, in jodhpurs and boots—
On guns, he's a bore
(Be they twelve, ten or four),
But he's worst when discussing his roots...

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
At her party I heard lots of chatter—
And none of it aiming to flatter.
Is she just overeating?
Or pregnant? Repeating
The question: Why's Kat so much fatter?

limerick_list.author: Roger Dunn
limerick_list.text:
Diving aircraft's a bit of a blast
Till your comfort-zone speed is surpassed.
To restore your enjoyment,
Slow down with deployment
Of dive brakes, then level off fast.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
Like the seldom-seen creature of fable,
The centaur is ready and able
To gallop past Zeus's
Great gravity-nooses,
And seldom approaches the stable.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
That's a lie! And I warn, with all candor,
To say it again  would be slander.
So I'm telling you, sport,
I will sue you in court —
Call me Mafia thug, not Black Hander.

limerick_list.author: Rich Ristow
limerick_list.text:
All the Earth always quakes when I grin,
And my face causes fights in Berlin.
(But that's false, not the truth.
I've been downing vermouth
And my boastful big mouth is my sin.)

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
This ship's false keel is shot — a disgrace;
It's been damaged in many a place.
My inspection's disclosed
That the real keel's exposed —
Repair or replace it apace!

limerick_list.author: Meg Beagle
limerick_list.text:
A lim'rick I find myself adding
When I'm far from that crowd yclept "madding."
There's time to immerse
Myself in new verse,
With plenty of meat—and less padding.

limerick_list.author: Harris Risman
limerick_list.text:
To Cervantes I say, "Don Miguel,
Don Quixote (your novel) is swell."
A delusional knight
With some windmills dares fight.
Reading nonsense has made him unwell.

limerick_list.author: Jim Vincent
limerick_list.text:
As classmates unevenly mated,
The senior and freshman debated.
The novice got beat,
Lacking substance and meat,
With his arguments frothily stated.

limerick_list.author: C. H. Carpenter
limerick_list.text:
The main anchor delivers our news
In a show to inform and amuse,
But that TV reporter
Can't lie or distort, or
Our confidence soon he will lose.

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
An art connoisseur in from Bali
Claimed that all modern art was sheer folly.
He came out of his coma
By visiting MoMA:
Au revoir to Renoir, hello Dali!

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
A bullhook can pierce a beast's hide.
It's a pole that's a pain in its side.
Yet trainers, those fools,
Use these inhumane tools
Just to break down an elephant's pride.

limerick_list.author: art bates
limerick_list.text:
She's a hockey fan true, that's my wife—
Really avid amid her team's strife.
The Canucks have long crashed,
But she states, unabashed,
That they'll bring home the Cup in this life.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
She's long been the star of her show,
And the line past her coffin moves slow.
Ms. O'Hair is at rest
With no need to be blessed—
All dressed up and with no place to go.

limerick_list.author: Jane Auerbach
limerick_list.text:
In Iraq, our troops living in CHUs
Have A/C, but they still get the blues.
CHUville quarters are roomy,
But troops still feel gloomy
Since news Bush should use says we'll lose.

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
Klein's Eternity, popular scent,
Owes its name to a famous event:
King Edward the Eighth
Pledged forever his faith
With a ring. Got the girl, kingdom went.

limerick_list.author: Richard English
limerick_list.text:
Chromium's a hard, brittle metal
That glistens like rain on a petal.
Bright chromium plate
On an auto looks great
And for years will remain in fine fettle.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Is the White House a large U.F.O.?
Does a man bathe his cat in Bordeaux?
Can a three-month-old baby
Speak Portuguese, maybe?
Disquisitive minds want to know!

limerick_list.author: waterrocks
limerick_list.text:
This system is closed: it forgoes
All transference; no energy flows
In or out of its bounds,
To or from its surrounds.
Inexorably, entropy grows.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
If you're craving a cheese that is new
To your palate, here's what you should do:
Try some Dura. It's graced
With a "mineral" taste.
(What exactly that means I've no clue.)

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
Now that purges don't take up their time,
The reformers are turning to crime.
So the people are storming
For counterreforming—
Restoring a peaceable clime.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
When a student calls, "Hey, Fred MacMurray!
Are you done with our papers?  No hurry!"
I think, "Papers? What class?
What's your name, you young ass?"
But my absentness causes me worry.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
I believe in dark spirits ethereal;
In the mornings, my diabaterial
Gift to the gods
To improve crossing odds
As a rule is hot gruel or dry cereal.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Let's explore this harsh coastline, my son.
Near the shoreline we'll climb, jump and run —
Even swim. It's endearing
You love co-coasteering
With me, cause it's double the fun.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
My wife shook her head, and said, "Brad,
Your changeableness is just mad.
You've been Chloe, then Drew,
Then you turned into Sue.
If you'd make up your mind, I'd be glad."

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Her commander begged all personnel
Of her caliber, "Don't say farewell
To your Army career!"
But depression, severe,
Made retention a very hard sell.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Cingalese is a tongue, hardly varied
In Ceylon, that's been faithfully carried
From father to son
Since before the Year One.
(It is not what you speak when unmarried.)

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
For large animals, vets use etorphine
To put them to sleep. Diprenorphine
Is needed to wake them,
So handlers can take them
To stalls, and then give them their morphine.

limerick_list.author: Roger Dunn
limerick_list.text:
Comet seekers are telescopes and
Are ideal when the heavens are scanned.
With their short focal length
And large aperture's strength,
The resultant bright image looks grand.

limerick_list.author: Dr. Work
limerick_list.text:
If you're craving a bowlful of Smacks,
Hit the cereal bars by the tracks.
But, frankly, I jest—
They're just cereal pressed
Into handy rectangular snacks.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
Whenever you sever an artery,
So you're bleeding and falling apartery,
And you bind it in vain,
Watch the spreading red stain,
A reminder it wasn't too smartery.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
From its looks, I could clearly deduce
That this diner was once a caboose.
Now no longer on tracks,
It's a place to buy snacks
Through what's known as adaptive reuse.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
With Onassis she lived in a palace—
The brilliant soprano, Ms. Callas.
Though some shouted "Viva,
Maria!," this diva
At times was disparaged with malice.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
My arrangements are daring, it's true,
But my vision you shan't misconstrue!
It's an unfounded myth
That my Beethoven's Fifth
Is for banjo and flute and kazoo!

limerick_list.author: mrsrev
limerick_list.text:
Billy Bob is a lout; he is clownish.
We hike upward while Billy hikes downish.
That clumperton! He
Is so silly to see!
He acts countryish shopping downtownish.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Aporia deals with confusion
In reaching a truthful conclusion.
What is truth?  What is not?
Is it substance we've got?
Or is it just passing illusion?

limerick_list.author: Richard English
limerick_list.text:
"Put brightness in all that you write,"
Said Pete, "for your words to excite.
Though the topic be serious,
Arcane or mysterious,
Writing that shine's a delight."

limerick_list.author: Peter Meyer
limerick_list.text:
"I am going to leave my old home,
To reside somewhere else," said Jerome,
"And although elocation
Requires acclimation,
I think I might like Puy-de-Dôme."

limerick_list.author: John Brevik
limerick_list.text:
Said a greedy young fellow from Devon,
"This behavior won't get me to heaven!
When my body's cadaverous,
My soul will burn!  Avarice,
As sins go, is surely Top Seven!"

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
Two new painkillers: Bayer had reckoned
That the first had a future that beckoned.
Diamorphine became
An exceptional shame;
They got riches and fame from the second.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
For obesity, Guy wins the prize.
"Can a surgeon excise, from his thighs
And his gut, excess fat?"
I inquire. "And would that
Mean he'd no longer wear an X-size?

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
Though I love little Fluffy to bits,
When I bathe her, I'll need heavy mitts.
For there's nothing, my dears,
That puts love in arrears
Like a white, long-haired cat with the squits.

limerick_list.author: bearybp
limerick_list.text:
Our conductor, who hailed from Honduras,
Had to finally quit and abjure us
For the cause of his woes
Was our arpeggios
And we murdered appoggiaturas.

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
In this dictionary entry of mine,
I have gloss meaning "lustre or shine".
In the margins, a gloss
Will help those at a loss—
You thought "phony appearance"? That's fine.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The comparison leaves me ecstatic:
First "of catalase"—that's catalatic.
Catalytic, the second,
Less specific, I've reckoned,
Any catalyst fits—how dramatic!

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
"Things look promising: truly auspicious.
That gal likes me; she's young and delicious.
She admires my brain
And my marvelous mane."
"Fool, you're hair-brained, and over-ambitious!"

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
If you want your home garden to grow,
You should break clumps of soil with a hoe.
Maybe plant some potatoes,
Green beans, or tomatoes.
(Marijuana's illegal, you know.)

limerick_list.author: Jeter Coffee
limerick_list.text:
The OEDILF is a fabulous site —
I've lingered at times half the night.
And should sleeplessness weigh
Down my eyelids next day,
I'll go back for more lim'rick delight.

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
By and large, it is true what they say:
Early birds get the worms, come what may.
Be it ever so humble,
A cookie will crumble.
Strike gold with a glitt'ring cliche.

limerick_list.author: Mary
limerick_list.text:
Clear-sightedly editing work
Of new writers means clearing the murk
From your vision of how
You'd revise it. For now,
Build rapport,  lest they think you're a jerk.

limerick_list.author: a.groovymind
limerick_list.text:
She thought she'd inherit Dad's gold;
But he threatened to cut her off cold.
All her hope of gold fled
When she heard his will read —
Dead serious words, truth be told.

limerick_list.author: Kevin
limerick_list.text:
Bigheartedness might bring success
When my lim's in a workshopping mess.
So, be liberal, don't cry,
When a weak rhyme comes by.
I'm not perfect; please practise largesse.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
If they can't sell a shot at the pub,
Then brown bagging it makes a good sub.
When you're looking to fix her
A drink, buy their mixer,
And add your own booze at the club.

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
If your loading boss asks you to count
All that's leaving the store, and this "fount
Of all wisdom" sends more
Than you're able to score,
That adds up to a copious amount.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Dated date, as a term, may sound funny,
But investments are serious, sonny.
If you purchase a bond
Since of interest you're fond,
It's your start date to earn money money.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
Said the boss, "Take the paint in this can.
Make a line down the road. That's the plan."
At day's end there were smiles
Since the line went eight miles.
"Do the same thing tomorrow then, Stan."

limerick_list.author: Jane Auerbach
limerick_list.text:
While the busboy was bussing our table,
We stopped kissing since I felt unable
To  buss in a place
Without space to embrace,
And where breadcrumbs might litter my sable.

limerick_list.author: birdbarf
limerick_list.text:
A brown bat (made of wood) once was bought
And then swung by the Sultan of Swat.
But this bat comes with wings,
Lives in caves, never swings,
And it relishes bugs that it's caught.

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
Ten prosperous nations agreed
To lend money, at times there was need,
To the IMF. Bet
That they like this new debt?
Not a lot, as I'm sure they'd concede.

limerick_list.author: man from tashkent
limerick_list.text:
When bones in one's bod suffer fracture
What's needed is action (or acture).
  Go summon a doc,
  Treat the patient for shock,
And then start up the cast manufacture.

limerick_list.author: Brian Cairns
limerick_list.text:
If to learn Aymara is your choice,
In Bolivia, discover your voice.
On the old Potosí line,
Way up past the treeline,
You'll meet folks to chat with—rejoice!

limerick_list.author: zqms
limerick_list.text:
Gastropteridae, small bat-winged slugs,
Are hermaphrodites. What looks like hugs
When they mate, is a fight —
Who'll be "mother" tonight?
What repulsive yet beautiful thugs.

limerick_list.author: Jane Auerbach
limerick_list.text:
My son Chad had to have a Pet Rock,
But the store said, "We ran out of stock.
They're back-ordered. Please wait—
We'll get more." How I hate
Such delays (and for this, it's a crock).

limerick_list.author: DenmarK
limerick_list.text:
The Copernican model does not
Put the Earth in the middle. That's what
Was once thought — how archaic,
With wheels Ptolemaic —
Not the Sun-centred system we've got.

limerick_list.author: Ruchiccio
limerick_list.text:
As my math teacher's graphing dilations,
The polygon's changing locations;
At first it looked small,
But it's now big and tall.
Soon we'll move on to more transformations.

limerick_list.author: Paul Wilmes
limerick_list.text:
"These giblets are really quite yummy;
You said they'd be bad for my tummy!"
"It's clear you misheard
A most critical word:
I told you they're 'offal,' you dummy!"

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin and mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
Half the chickens in Chuck's chicken coop
Had been ailing; he thought it was croup.
So he slaughtered a hen
Who was healthy, and then
He could feed all the rest chicken soup.

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
Colestyramine acts like a sponge
For bile, which your gut can expunge.
So your liver makes more
From the stuff that's in store,
And cholesterol levels then plunge.

limerick_list.author: cauliflower
limerick_list.text:
If you fancy yourself as a tugger
Of other men's shirttails, a hugger
Of other men's bums
In formations called scrums,
Play the game whose apt name rhymes with bugger.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Said Jacques Derrida, "Let's deconstruct
The world's lit'rature. Then we'll conduct
A new journey to knowledge.
We'll teach it in college;
The old ways of thinking we've chucked!"

limerick_list.author: Virge
limerick_list.text:
Altaic has caused much ado.
It's a language group some would eschew.
They would deem hyperbolic
Claims linking Mongolic
To Tungusic and Turkic tongues too.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
As a writer/performer, his powers
Excelled; we'd be laughing for hours!
Monty Python was great
And John Cleese was first rate,
But my favorite of all? Fawlty Towers.

limerick_list.author: Dr. Work
limerick_list.text:
Hobo Bob was not one to conform,
So a coal car he used as his dorm.
But one day they dumped coal
In that car—the poor soul!
(Though he did want to go someplace warm…)

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
She's the final girl still in contention,
With grace and astounding extension:
Her foot poised overhead.
If she does that in bed,
She's in line for a chunk of my pension.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Cryalgesia's pain, I am told,
That results from the presence of cold.
You'd feel it if you
From a hot tub withdrew
And then into a snowbank were rolled.

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
"Moody Carla, my lover, is vain."
That's a phrase I had better explain—
There's a chronogram there,
So please study with care.
Want the year of my birth? Use your brain!

limerick_list.author: Michael Toalster
limerick_list.text:
I engaged to assist my friend Joe
To sell knee-cap replacements "to go".
Yes, I promised I'd do
All the marketing too,
But a drive-thru? I had to say no.

limerick_list.author: RCK
limerick_list.text:
Sal Sweeney's the adjunct professor,
Called "adjunct" because he's the lesser
Or assistant lit. prof.,
Obligated to doff
His cap and to answer, "Why yes, sir!"

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
Send a message, I'll text you right back!
Like a coke head addicted to crack,
I'm a Crackberry slave,
Craving networks that save
Precious time and eliminate slack.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
When craters disfigure terrain,
At times they align in a chain.
In the crater arena,
A chain's a catena.
The causes? Mundane to arcane.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
The Fifties had slang we should mention:
Some phrases of teenage invention.
To your buddy or pal
('Cept of course, if a gal) —
"Hey, daddy-o!" got his attention.

limerick_list.author: Chuck Folkers
limerick_list.text:
Gordon Bennett went down to the pub,
Where he met with the Euphemists Club.
At their quarterly meeting,
The members were beating
The bushes for curse words to scrub.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"Hello, Dolly!" has caused me to drink so,
And to twitch and to jerk and to blink so.
It's too much, I submit!
Can you name one more hit
Carol Channing has sung? (Didn't think so!)

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Bill's in love, yes, I know, but there's trouble.
While I don't want to burst Billy's bubble,
If a date should run long,
He might note something wrong
When he kisses her cheek and feels stubble.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
In a castle lived young Mistress Glover
And spouse.  He was shocked to discover
A man in his place
With a smile on his face;
In their bed lay the chatelaine's lover.

limerick_list.author: Mark Mironer
limerick_list.text:
On my Czechoslovakian trek,
Met a native (quite long in the neck).
So I traded a snack
For a ride on his back.
You could say that I rode a lank Czech.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
The coyote brush spreads itself wide
In the desert where animals hide.
It's an evergreen shrub,
Not your everyday scrub,
Having flowery shows to provide.

limerick_list.author: stella
limerick_list.text:
My neuroses are varied and deep
And include chirophobia; keep
At a distance because
The mere thought of your paws
Makes me stressed and unable to sleep.

limerick_list.author: neilski
limerick_list.text:
"Come back and say that to my face!"
But he pulled a disdainful grimace.
So I called his full name,
And he crept back in shame.
He was sent to his room in disgrace.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Meryl warns us, in Canine Domingo,
A film filled with Down Under lingo,
Of the horrors of teething.
Scene One, Streep is seething:
"Your babies have eaten my dingo!"

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Roads are wet, then they freeze and black ice
Is a danger, so take my advice:
Drive with care lest you skid,
And then crash—as I  did.
Now I'm cautious; it won't happen twice.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
Though your monkey's a tripe-writing whiz,
You'll be selling your business as is.
"Piss-poor future," you gripe,
"Owning monkeys that type,
Since computers are wrecking the biz!"

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Cloister quarters are tiny and spare.
And the meals? Call them limited fare.
This old cellulary housing's
No place for carousings:
Loads of topics for grousing or prayer.

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
A corpulent man went and sat
By a girl who deflated him flat
When he asked her to dance:
"Are you nuts? Not a chance!
You're not only too old, pal—you're fat."

limerick_list.author: John Wellington Wells
limerick_list.text:
He's five children, two dogs, and a cat;
Loves his job, collects rugs, wears a hat.
So in short say of him
His life's filled to the brim—
And so too, I might add, is his flat.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
Paper bags and some tape — it's a breeze,
And protects you from book-damage fees.
But before paper bags,
Cloth or leather (no rags)
Made a book cover called a chemise.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
When lawsuits make docs apprehensive,
Their medicine's often  defensive.
Each unwarranted test
Is expensive at best,
And at worst can cause harm that's extensive.

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
The scene of this sad song balladic
Is my great great great aunty's back paddock,
Where, as told in this verse,
The old bag lost her purse.
(It's called "Who in the Hell Stole my Haddock?")

limerick_list.author: Frank Luke
limerick_list.text:
Eastern cooking will call for this spice,
Whose smell and rich taste are so nice.
When mulling some wine,
And you want something fine,
Let some cardamom flavor suffice.

limerick_list.author: Rudi
limerick_list.text:
Though wolves can be known by their howl,
And quacks are the trademark of fowl;
Though cows love to moo,
And men might sing doo-
Wop, they'd all stop upon a bear's growl.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
A dessert apple's one you don't bake,
But eat raw, although make no mistake:
While an apple a day
For dessert is OK,
Even doctors prefer chocolate cake.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Using methods completely my own,
From a rock, I've conclusively shown
I can draw a slight flow
Of the red stuff—type O!
So you can extract blood from a stone.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
"Where señoras still wear a mantilla
(Down in Baja) I've heard there may be a
Tree where elephants grow.
Man, I'll bet they hang low."
"No, the tree yields a folk panacea."

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
Said Elsie, a cunning old elf,
As she stole my most decorative shelf,
"I would craft one from wood,
But my skills are no good,
So I'm craftily helping myself."

limerick_list.author: Amergin
limerick_list.text:
Cut your speed and shunt right, then advance.
Let it feed, keep it tight, take no chance.
When the down train has passed,
You reverse at long last,
'Til your backbone's the tunnel to France.

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
When a boom-chuck-chuck boom-chuck-chuck beat
Makes you whirlish and light on your feet,
Then you're dancing a waltz.
It's some Viennese schmaltz!
Can Johann-dle this musical treat?

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
One can spend a dependable coin
In Detroit or Duluth or Des Moines.
But whenever they pay
With a slug, one should say,
"Here's a three-dollar bill in retoin."

limerick_list.author: Bit
limerick_list.text:
This kimono plant's flowers appear
To resemble gloxinias, dear.
It's a tropical herb
And its flowers?  Superb.
An Achimenes; that much is clear!

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
My new poetry's bold and aggressive,
Full of meaning and feeling (expressive),
Which is why readers cry,
And no eye remains dry—
But drink iodine? That seems excessive.

limerick_list.author: Mary and mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
On a slow boat to China we dallied;
I asked why your face looked so pallid.
You replied, "It's so far,
Yet the rising red star
Is alarming." How prescient and valid!

limerick_list.author: Chavi Beck
limerick_list.text:
The dish I invented tonight
Gets the random additions just right.
Secret flavorings spike it...
Oh, try it. You'll like it!
I'm calling it "Tuna Delight."

limerick_list.author: Edmund Conti
limerick_list.text:
Castling is hard to explain
If you don't have a chess-playing brain.
The king swaps with the rook
And unless I'm mistook...
Oh, never mind, please take a rain-

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
Adding batteries and bulbs to a worm
Will result in no light, just a squirm,
For everyone knows
That a glow-worm that glows
Is a beetle. On that I stand firm.

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
Rhinoplasty's my game, and it blows
(Though proctology's worse, I suppose).
What I find so deplorable
And plain unignorable:
Damned patients keep picking their nose.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
The Book-of-the-Month Club's succeeding
In ways that you might think misleading.
Books on Tape are the way
To make profits today
In a world in which nobody's reading!

limerick_list.author: timon
limerick_list.text:
That there shootin's a dangerous hobby:
You'll remember the death of Cock Robbie.
How did a young sparrow
Obtain bow and arrow?
It's the fault of the NRA lobby.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
I'm a man who routinely inspects
What I hide with my private effects.
I like seeing the flash
Of the jewelry I stash
In the place where I also cache checks.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Is this huge South American food fish,
Arapaima, a dominant brood fish?
When he calls on his mate
For a freshwater date,
Does she ever play not-in-the-mood fish?

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The new prof, here a year, won't be staying.
The chairman delayed his okaying.
He was rated, belatedly:
"He speaks complicatedly,
And nobody knows what he's saying."

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
When he begged to, just once, share her bed:
"In your dreams, pig. I'd rather be dead!"
Still, his hope springs eternally:
He pursues her — infernally,
Determinedly stumbling ahead.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Funny money is going around.
In my wallet I've got some, I found.
"Here in London," I moan,
"Any fool should have known
Adolf Hitler is not on the pound."

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The chilopod fills me with fright.
I'm afraid of its poisonous bite.
The time I most dread?
When I get into bed,
As the chilopod's active at night.

limerick_list.author: Dr. Work
limerick_list.text:
I once knew a corpsman named Sam,
Who had served as a medic in 'Nam.
Any guy who got shot,
If he liked it or not,
Would be given a rectal exam.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Weather's nuts; these are fast changing times,
As the temperature crashes, then climbs.
These were equable shores;
Now we're sheltered indoors.
Nature's punishing us for our crimes.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"There's a rumor I heard that you're blue,
So I've come here to cheerfulize you."
Just my use of that word,
Since it sounds so absurd,
Brought a smile, so I bowed and withdrew.

limerick_list.author: Recumbentman
limerick_list.text:
Through philosophy, darkest of crafts,
Shine Dan Dennett's enlightening shafts.
His consciousness theory
Is hearty and beery:
He takes it in multiple drafts.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
I gave you the shirt off my back;
You're not worth it — you phony, you quack.
So now I am shirtless
And you're still desertless —
You really deserve a good smack.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
She was foaled with such startling force
That a howitzer seemed an apt source,
So we thought of Krupp's gun:
Western Front, World War I,
And we named her Big Bertha, of course.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
"He loves me," she says, "loves me not."
And she pulls off a petal. Then what
Does she find—lovesick Maisie?—
A dipetalous daisy.
"Where was I?" she cries. "I forgot!"

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
So I said to the handyman, "Dan'l,
You don't need a whole flippin' panel
Of experts! Real quick,
Get your shovel and pick,
And then canalize—dig me a channel!"

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
The leaf of a pig is called flare.
I should give you some clue as to where
I am talking about,
So, to banish all doubt,
It's the fat round the kidneys I share.

limerick_list.author: Roger Dunn
limerick_list.text:
It's behaviour I cannot condone:
When a diner whose musical phone
Sounds a jingly alert
While I eat my dessert.
I think, Go! Dine alfresco alone.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Rodney caught me flat-footed today.
He surprised me — said, "Let's run away!"
I replied, "If you're hoping
We'll soon be eloping,
Not yet, although groping's OK."

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Fanny Brice wore the clothes of a child
And proceeded to drive "Daddy" wild.
Baby Snooks, on the air,
Was a character rare:
We were cheered, entertained, and beguiled.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
There's a typo in Grandma's obit.
"She was fat," so they say, meaning "fit."
At that libelous phrase,
I was laughing for days.
Things like that crack me up, I admit.

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
Look, why don't you take a bo-peep
At the shed, where the shivering sheep
Have been shorn of their wool—
Maybe three whole bags full—
And are so bloody cold they've lost sleep.

limerick_list.author: Joanna Keene
limerick_list.text:
In masses of work he's been mired,
And he fears that he soon might be fired.
The economy's slow,
With some colleagues let go—
He's enervate: exhausted, plum tired.

limerick_list.author: oneslowtyper
limerick_list.text:
This country's amassing a debt
That will burden our kids, you can bet.
When the debtors come calling
And stocks are free-falling,
The rich will be offshore and set.

limerick_list.author: J. E. Pettit
limerick_list.text:
He's got gemstones to sell on the sly
That he's hoping you're willing to buy.
Just ignore the details:
All those blood diamond sales
Pay for battles where innocents die.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
From one action, results are direct
In the domino (ripple) effect.
Though each change may be small,
Set in motion are all
The events that will interconnect.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
Night oarsmen in water. A strand.
Ashore, ten, I'm warranting, stand.
Here, they have no old rope,
Or they'd leave her no hope:
Their anagram's written on sand.

limerick_list.author: LL Crutchfield
limerick_list.text:
Asked a chaplain one day, "Are you churched?"
Of a man who beside his wife perched
On a pew before service.
The man looked quite nervous.
"Not for long," he decided and lurched.

limerick_list.author: Beverley Sharp
limerick_list.text:
Crafting limericks takes cogitation
(That means "thinking") and metric frustration.
To get out of this jam,
I think, therefore, iamb!
Won't these anapests take a vacation?

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
There's a rabbi who's sly as a fox,
But his crimes give the rebbetzin shocks.
She expects he'd finagle
Cream cheese and a bagel,
But burgle? The guy can pick lox!

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
No cur, hound or courser belongs
In a church. My extensible tongs
(Known as dog tongs) can grip
Dogs so tight they can't slip —
See those jaws, with their long, toothy prongs?

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
My hamster-sized primate's no schemer
But quite a productive small dreamer.
Sarah Zehr says it's clear:
Snoozing half of the year
Means long life for my fat-tailed dwarf lemur.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
When it's name derivations I seek,
I find days' names are ancient—antique!
There are Thor, Frigg, and Tyr,
Also Wodan, I fear:
Pagan gods for each day of the week.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
While ahold of my wife on the phone,
In the background I heard a man moan.
All the while she was speaking,
I heard the bed creaking.
I'm thinking she wasn't alone!

limerick_list.author: turnip
limerick_list.text:
What the heck is a BFOQ?
It lets bishops be forthright with you:
One who seeks to be priest
Must be Catholic, at least;
It's no job for a girl who's a Jew.

limerick_list.author: Carole Lyons
MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
"Please take care; of this merger be chary —
Be cautious, I'm urgin'!" cried Cary.
"St. Peter is mergin',
With Mary The Virgin,
And rules for such church-mergin' vary."

limerick_list.author: Fleur De Lim
limerick_list.text:
Throat's all raw after bouts of much hacking;
Nose streaming, sore head feels like cracking—
I'm one frightful mess
In the depths of distress!
Hey, one good thing—this cold curbed my snacking!

limerick_list.author: Roger Vick
limerick_list.text:
Your carrots in storage will mold
If the cottony soft rot takes hold.
To a major degree
Sanitation is key—
And a temperature suitably cold.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
The deer dance, not popular here,
Might bring jeers from observers, I fear.
It's a folk dance that's found
Many spots the world round
Where the dancer's disguised as a deer.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
Coca Cola — shake up a whole case;
 CO2 bubbles up every place.
Yeah, decarbonate soda
And stay for the coda —
The bottles explode in your face.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
No power. Its styling? Low-key.
A heater? Defroster? Tee-hee.
The Volkswagen Bug
Gives my heartstrings a tug,
And it drove from point A to point B.

limerick_list.author: Chuck Folkers
limerick_list.text:
Geoinformatics addresses location
And data whose interrelation
Is graphically shown
As a map, which I'm prone
To prefer to the raw information.
